WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
[Amit Varma]: The days are long, but the years are short. When a year ends, as 2022 is ending soon,

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:14.320
[Amit Varma]: it's a good time to sit back and take stock. But for this year-ending episode, I didn't

00:00:14.320 --> 00:00:19.440
[Amit Varma]: want big serious subjects, ponderous self-reflection, laments about the state of the world. Instead,

00:00:19.440 --> 00:00:23.360
[Amit Varma]: I wanted to sit and take stock of all the things that should give us hope. I wanted

00:00:23.360 --> 00:00:27.200
[Amit Varma]: life lessons that could inspire us to move forward. I often speak of hope and despair

00:00:27.200 --> 00:00:31.520
[Amit Varma]: on this show. Well, in this episode, I wanted you and me to feel hopeful at the end of it.

00:00:31.520 --> 00:00:35.840
[Amit Varma]: And boy, am I happy with the two friends I called on and the conversation we had.

00:00:35.840 --> 00:00:39.440
[Amit Varma]: This was one of my most enjoyable conversations. And when I heard it back,

00:00:39.440 --> 00:00:43.040
[Amit Varma]: I was blown away by the amount of wisdom that these two guests brought to the table,

00:00:43.040 --> 00:00:46.960
[Amit Varma]: which I hadn't even noticed while recording because we were so busy having a blast.

00:00:46.960 --> 00:00:51.120
[Amit Varma]: Now, I know this was a long episode, but my last episode to go over 7 hours,

00:00:51.120 --> 00:00:54.480
[Amit Varma]: episode 303 with Nikhil Taneja, the loneliness of the Indian man,

00:00:54.480 --> 00:00:58.640
[Amit Varma]: touched so many people so deeply that I'm still getting emails about it. I mean,

00:00:58.640 --> 00:01:02.480
[Amit Varma]: I only go long when the conversation is so great that we lose track of time.

00:01:02.480 --> 00:01:07.120
[Amit Varma]: So do listen to this episode as well, in parts if you have to. When you reach the end,

00:01:07.120 --> 00:01:13.360
[Amit Varma]: I promise you'll ask, hey, why did it end so soon? But hey, 2022 is also ending so soon.

00:01:13.360 --> 00:01:17.360
[Amit Varma]: But let's enjoy the years ahead of us and the many conversations ahead of us.

00:01:17.360 --> 00:01:25.040
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics,

00:01:25.040 --> 00:01:29.280
[Unknown]: politics and behavioral science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:33.520 --> 00:01:37.440
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen. My guests today for the special year-end episode are my

00:01:37.440 --> 00:01:42.080
[Amit Varma]: good friends Vikram Sathe and Roshan Abbas. Now, if I try to give Roshan the introduction he

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:48.080
[Amit Varma]: deserves, that only will take 7 hours. He's a radio star, a TV star, an events mogul, a filmmaker,

00:01:48.080 --> 00:01:52.800
[Amit Varma]: an entrepreneur and today, a mentor and an inspiration to young creators everywhere

00:01:52.800 --> 00:01:57.280
[Amit Varma]: and older ones like me. But most of all, at least for me, he's a good human being

00:01:57.280 --> 00:02:01.600
[Amit Varma]: who makes me also want to be a better person. He's been on the show before, and I urge you

00:02:01.600 --> 00:02:06.000
[Amit Varma]: to check out that earlier episode as well, in which he talks about his life, his learnings

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:10.160
[Amit Varma]: and the creator economy. In this episode, we spoke more about his life and learnings,

00:02:10.160 --> 00:02:14.560
[Amit Varma]: and he spoke about what he learnt and unlearned while playing the role of Lalit Verma in the

00:02:14.560 --> 00:02:20.080
[Amit Varma]: musical version of Monsoon Wedding, which is going to Broadway soon. How Meera Nair taught him to have

00:02:20.080 --> 00:02:26.400
[Amit Varma]: the heart of a poet and the skin of an elephant. And how, as Roshan keeps telling me, one must

00:02:26.400 --> 00:02:33.200
[Amit Varma]: either be interested or be interesting. And to me, Roshan is both of those, which is why he makes for

00:02:33.200 --> 00:02:38.800
[Amit Varma]: such a delightful guest. My other guest today is my old buddy Vikram Sathe, also known variously

00:02:38.800 --> 00:02:44.240
[Amit Varma]: as Baljeet and Parpeetaram, who was my contemporary in Ferguson College, Pune in the early 1990s,

00:02:44.240 --> 00:02:48.720
[Amit Varma]: and later my colleague at MTV in the mid to late 90s. He worked in marketing then,

00:02:48.720 --> 00:02:53.920
[Amit Varma]: which was kind of at odds with his past as a budding musician, singer and cricketer. Now,

00:02:53.920 --> 00:02:59.440
[Amit Varma]: one of his side skills then was comedy, and one subset of his comedy skills was mimicry. He soon

00:02:59.440 --> 00:03:03.680
[Amit Varma]: got known for that, entertained people with his stand-up act on cricket, and what was timepass

00:03:03.680 --> 00:03:09.200
[Amit Varma]: at parties became a profession. A decade before India's stand-up explosion, Vikram was doing sold

00:03:09.200 --> 00:03:14.560
[Amit Varma]: out shows and corporate events and did literally thousands of performances. He also got into cricket

00:03:14.560 --> 00:03:18.560
[Amit Varma]: broadcasting and became good friends with top cricketers, just as he already was with top

00:03:18.560 --> 00:03:24.000
[Amit Varma]: artists. He's one person I know who was close to both the Tendulkars, Vijay Tendulkar and Sachin

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:30.000
[Amit Varma]: Tendulkar, and one of his great skills was in imbibing life lessons from everyone he came

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:34.320
[Amit Varma]: across. He did this from both Tendulkars, he wrote a best-selling book about his journey,

00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:38.800
[Amit Varma]: and then made a wildly successful YouTube show, What the Duck with Vikram Sathe,

00:03:38.800 --> 00:03:42.560
[Amit Varma]: in which he spoke to top cricketers and revealed the way they think for all of us.

00:03:43.120 --> 00:03:47.680
[Amit Varma]: Besides his comedy and his YouTubing, he also became a top motivational speaker,

00:03:47.680 --> 00:03:52.000
[Amit Varma]: and now spends time investing his hard-earned money, paying it back as it were.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:56.240
[Amit Varma]: I've always loved three qualities of Vikram which I try to work on for myself. One,

00:03:56.240 --> 00:04:01.600
[Amit Varma]: his constant curiosity about the world. Two, his humility, despite his many achievements,

00:04:01.600 --> 00:04:06.400
[Amit Varma]: which always keeps him open to learning into new experiences. And three, his good humour,

00:04:06.400 --> 00:04:10.640
[Amit Varma]: the positive energy that keeps him moving forward. And hey, coming to think of it,

00:04:10.640 --> 00:04:14.400
[Amit Varma]: Roshan shares these qualities as well. We explored Vikram's journey in this episode,

00:04:14.400 --> 00:04:18.000
[Amit Varma]: in which he shared his learnings from Bollywood, from the corporate world, from sport,

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:22.800
[Amit Varma]: and as Roshan did as well, from life. This is one of the most enjoyable conversations I've

00:04:22.800 --> 00:04:27.840
[Amit Varma]: ever had on the show, not least because of the feast of singing towards the end.

00:04:27.840 --> 00:04:55.680
[Amit Varma]: Just wonderful. But before we begin, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:04:57.840 --> 00:05:21.680
[Amit Varma]: So if you're interested, head on over to register at indiauncut.com slash clear writing.

00:05:21.680 --> 00:05:27.280
[Amit Varma]: That's indiauncut.com slash clear writing. Being a good writer doesn't require God given talent,

00:05:27.280 --> 00:05:32.880
[Amit Varma]: just a willingness to work hard and a clear idea of what you need to do to refine your skills.

00:05:32.880 --> 00:05:33.680
[Amit Varma]: I can help you.

00:05:37.920 --> 00:05:40.000
[Amit Varma]: Roshan and Vikram, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:05:40.800 --> 00:05:42.160
[Amit Varma]: Fabulous to be here with you again.

00:05:42.880 --> 00:05:47.200
[Guest 2]: Thank you Amit for having me. 30 years I've known you, finally you've given me some respect.

00:05:49.760 --> 00:05:56.080
[Amit Varma]: Okay, that's a good way to start. So let me start by sort of bringing up an interesting

00:05:56.080 --> 00:06:02.960
[Amit Varma]: observation. Yesterday I saw this tweet from Tim Urban basically to the effect of how when you are

00:06:02.960 --> 00:06:08.800
[Amit Varma]: young, you have no money, but lots of time. And as you get older, when you get to the age that we are,

00:06:08.800 --> 00:06:13.360
[Amit Varma]: you have the money problem is hopefully solved, you have more money, but you have less time,

00:06:13.360 --> 00:06:17.440
[Amit Varma]: time is a scarce resource. And you know, Paul Graham replied to this, you know,

00:06:17.440 --> 00:06:21.280
[Amit Varma]: from an investment point of view saying that when you're building something for the young,

00:06:21.280 --> 00:06:24.960
[Amit Varma]: remember that they have no money, but they have time and vice versa for older people.

00:06:24.960 --> 00:06:31.040
[Amit Varma]: And I was kind of just wondering, you know, given that we are sort of middle aged,

00:06:31.040 --> 00:06:34.480
[Amit Varma]: so I shouldn't, you know, say Roshan is already looking upset because he's young.

00:06:35.760 --> 00:06:42.720
[Amit Varma]: Given that we are, you know, late 40s, early 50s, you know, how would you sort of think about,

00:06:42.720 --> 00:06:47.040
[Amit Varma]: think about this? Like, how has this changed what you do now, as opposed to you know,

00:06:47.040 --> 00:06:48.320
[Amit Varma]: how you lived your lives when you were young?

00:06:48.320 --> 00:06:54.560
[Guest 1]: So, see, personally, I completely agree with the fact of saying that time becomes a scarce resource

00:06:54.560 --> 00:07:01.920
[Guest 1]: over a period of time, I mean, as you age, but somehow, if you really need to keep optimize time

00:07:01.920 --> 00:07:07.280
[Guest 1]: and expand it, the first thing that I started doing very early was I make myself redundant in

00:07:07.280 --> 00:07:12.880
[Guest 1]: every job that I do. I immediately very quickly find a replacement, teach them what I know and

00:07:12.880 --> 00:07:18.320
[Guest 1]: very quickly find a replacement, teach them what I know and move on. Because that's when I again find

00:07:18.320 --> 00:07:22.080
[Guest 1]: that free time available. During the pandemic, I hired two people, I call them my left brain,

00:07:22.080 --> 00:07:28.880
[Guest 1]: my right brain. And both of these guys actually do 150% of what I do, because 50% of what they do

00:07:28.880 --> 00:07:33.040
[Guest 1]: is stuff I could never do. I'm not good with finance, I'm not very, very good with follow

00:07:33.040 --> 00:07:38.400
[Guest 1]: up on a couple of things. You know, if you really need to analyze things, I react far more, you know,

00:07:38.400 --> 00:07:42.400
[Guest 1]: from a creative perspective, I love the idea, but I may not think so much about the execution.

00:07:42.400 --> 00:07:48.080
[Guest 1]: So all of these, you know, so they were able to take that on, they are one is 25, one is 24.

00:07:48.080 --> 00:07:53.600
[Guest 1]: You know, so I've actually, that's how I'm trying to optimize it to a certain degree. But I do feel

00:07:53.600 --> 00:07:58.960
[Guest 1]: that these two concepts, I mean, if you have to constantly look at life from money and, you know,

00:07:58.960 --> 00:08:04.720
[Guest 1]: time perspective, I somehow really look at it a little differently. I'm always just trying to see

00:08:04.720 --> 00:08:11.040
[Guest 1]: that, can you make your life richer in any way, whether it is meeting up with friends,

00:08:11.040 --> 00:08:14.640
[Guest 1]: catching up on conversation, whether it's reading, whether it's writing, whether it's,

00:08:14.640 --> 00:08:18.240
[Guest 1]: you know, going out and doing a play or doing whatever else. But I just think, you know,

00:08:18.240 --> 00:08:22.160
[Guest 1]: I think I'm just a huge enthusiast of jumping into doing things in life.

00:08:23.840 --> 00:08:28.480
[Guest 1]: Time expands or contracts to fill the space, I think, you know, as work does at the same time.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:34.960
[Guest 2]: Yeah, so this doesn't apply to me, because I don't see any change in me over the last

00:08:34.960 --> 00:08:39.600
[Guest 2]: 48 years that I'm alive. Because for me, as I mentioned to you in the beginning,

00:08:39.600 --> 00:08:46.400
[Guest 2]: Amit that my desire was not there. So nothing changed drastically. If I was at eight years,

00:08:46.400 --> 00:08:51.680
[Guest 2]: a certain mindset, which is low attention span, doing whatever's going on on a daily basis. This

00:08:51.680 --> 00:08:56.960
[Guest 2]: is exactly how I live today. There was this eight years in corporate life, that I was a little bit

00:08:56.960 --> 00:09:01.840
[Guest 2]: different because it was a nine to nine routine. After that, I got back to my childhood. So the

00:09:01.840 --> 00:09:07.280
[Guest 2]: transition of going into a corporate job was the only aberration for eight years. After that,

00:09:07.280 --> 00:09:14.480
[Guest 2]: I'm back because I'm a freelancer. And for me, I've realized that do little, get more output.

00:09:14.480 --> 00:09:19.040
[Guest 2]: If you can crack that I have enough and more time for me. So honestly, I can't answer this

00:09:19.040 --> 00:09:22.080
[Guest 2]: question because I have no thoughts I have, I've remained exactly the same.

00:09:22.960 --> 00:09:28.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, you mentioned earlier at breakfast that you don't remember anything. So, you know,

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:32.640
[Amit Varma]: every day is a new day. But even then, I mean, the question of no desire, I mean,

00:09:32.640 --> 00:09:37.520
[Amit Varma]: I kind of get it in the sense that many people have these long arching ambitions,

00:09:39.280 --> 00:09:44.720
[Amit Varma]: and fine, you don't have that. But nevertheless, you have some desires, which is why you kind of

00:09:44.720 --> 00:09:49.120
[Amit Varma]: have the kind of career that you've had, even if you didn't actively plan it out or chase it that

00:09:49.120 --> 00:09:55.520
[Amit Varma]: way. So was it just like a series of what was your sort of philosophy and looking back philosophy,

00:09:55.520 --> 00:10:00.320
[Amit Varma]: looking back, but not thinking about it or framing it that way? Was it really a thing of just do

00:10:00.320 --> 00:10:04.800
[Amit Varma]: whatever makes you happy in the moment or jo hoga so hoga? Absolutely. And that came from a fact

00:10:04.800 --> 00:10:09.200
[Guest 2]: that I was exposed to a lot of things. I played cricket for Maharashtra, I played, you know,

00:10:09.200 --> 00:10:14.400
[Guest 2]: my mother's a classical musician. So all the cultural aspects were there. So I was getting

00:10:14.400 --> 00:10:19.280
[Guest 2]: this base level happiness any which way. So I didn't have to do ki aage jaake merko yeh concert

00:10:19.280 --> 00:10:25.120
[Guest 2]: dekhna hai. Sab mere paas tha so I didn't feel any deep desire to do anything. But at that moment,

00:10:25.120 --> 00:10:29.040
[Guest 2]: I felt ki yaar yeh karke dekhte hain. So there's a difference. I didn't have any specific desire,

00:10:29.040 --> 00:10:32.800
[Guest 2]: but I was curious. Yeh majdaar hai, yeh karke dekhte hain, yeh bhi karte hain. So

00:10:32.800 --> 00:10:36.560
[Guest 2]: in that moment, I was getting my happiness. So why do I have to change the world?

00:10:36.560 --> 00:10:40.560
[Amit Varma]: That was the core philosophy. So you know, Roshan's been on my show before,

00:10:40.560 --> 00:10:45.200
[Amit Varma]: and we've explored his childhood and adulthood and so on. I won't say middle age.

00:10:47.200 --> 00:10:50.560
[Guest 1]: Though I still believe that we were cheated by that recordist of all our time. Because

00:10:50.560 --> 00:10:53.520
[Guest 1]: just as you're getting into the flow of things, he says, I need to sanitize the studio,

00:10:53.520 --> 00:10:59.040
[Guest 1]: I've got a recording at 10. Aur 9 baj gaya tha. I was just like, abhi toh baat shuru hoi thi.

00:11:01.040 --> 00:11:06.160
[Amit Varma]: So what basically happened was that Roshan and I did one of those few early recordings before I set

00:11:06.160 --> 00:11:10.960
[Amit Varma]: up my home studio. So I had booked out a studio and I'd taken my four, five hours or whatever

00:11:10.960 --> 00:11:15.520
[Amit Varma]: there. And it was at night. So I assumed ki agar thora extent kar liya, toh theek hai paise waise

00:11:15.520 --> 00:11:20.880
[Amit Varma]: de denge, but time mil jayega. Paisa and time again. But they said, no, no, there's a recording

00:11:20.880 --> 00:11:27.840
[Amit Varma]: at 10pm. And I'm still suspicious ki bhai kya tha, kaun aa raha tha 10 pajay. But yeah, so we only

00:11:27.840 --> 00:11:32.560
[Guest 1]: had a four hour conversation, which was very sad. But we should... Again, because with Amit,

00:11:32.560 --> 00:11:37.840
[Guest 1]: those conversations just keep, they can go on. I think if somebody offered to sleep the night here,

00:11:37.840 --> 00:11:41.760
[Guest 1]: woh do din tak chalta rahega. Woh banega, ek 48 hours banne wala hai. Toh yeh hum koshish

00:11:41.760 --> 00:11:46.640
[Guest 2]: karenge abhi. Aur ek interesting tha jab Amit ka email aaya, toh mujhe ek feeling aisa aaya hai ki

00:11:46.640 --> 00:11:51.680
[Guest 2]: the way he had, you know, communicated to us, I got a feeling that abhi intellectuals bahut ho

00:11:51.680 --> 00:11:59.120
[Unknown]: gayi. Let me lower the benchmark. Let me lower the benchmark of the show, so that next year,

00:12:03.920 --> 00:12:10.720
[Amit Varma]: no, but you know, that's, that's partly what I was aiming for in the sense that not, not that

00:12:10.720 --> 00:12:14.000
[Unknown]: intellectuals bahut ho gayi, they'll all be listening to this and thinking what bahut ho gayi,

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:19.200
[Amit Varma]: mere saath 5 ghante baat kiya. But simply because I think a lot of what happens is a lot of our

00:12:19.200 --> 00:12:23.920
[Amit Varma]: conversations get damn serious and you're lamenting the state of the country and all of that, which

00:12:23.920 --> 00:12:30.400
[Amit Varma]: deserves to be lamented. But at the same time, I think that sometimes you also need to celebrate

00:12:30.400 --> 00:12:34.080
[Amit Varma]: the little things that are there and not so much as celebrate in terms of har cheez mein aap

00:12:34.080 --> 00:12:40.640
[Amit Varma]: positive dhundo. But just that, you know, I think all of us have in different ways found, you know,

00:12:40.640 --> 00:12:45.520
[Amit Varma]: figured out ways to make sense of the world, find happiness for ourselves. And it's interesting to

00:12:45.520 --> 00:12:51.440
[Amit Varma]: sort of for me to look back on that, share the good things and talk about that. And so Vikram,

00:12:51.440 --> 00:12:56.240
[Unknown]: had you had a very tragic life, I may not have called you here, ki kaun sunna chhata hai yaar,

00:12:56.240 --> 00:13:01.920
[Unknown]: ki I was impoverished at the age of eight, main matlab nal chowk pe bheek maangta tha.

00:13:01.920 --> 00:13:11.200
[Guest 2]: Jaise maine bola tha ki impoverished hoon, probably tha, magar main bhool gaya. So as I've told you that my ability to forget what's

00:13:11.200 --> 00:13:16.640
[Guest 2]: happened in the past, as I told Roshan and you in the morning, that I one day made a list of people

00:13:16.640 --> 00:13:22.160
[Guest 2]: ki inse mujhe badla lena hai, badla ki aag mere. And I forgot why they had done bad things to me.

00:13:22.160 --> 00:13:24.960
[Guest 2]: So then I decided to cancel the badla. And then he forgot the list also.

00:13:24.960 --> 00:13:32.800
[Guest 2]: And I think that is the secret to happiness, low attention span and less memory.

00:13:34.720 --> 00:13:39.680
[Amit Varma]: In the manifestations, which you mentioned it, but I'm sure not by themselves, like Roshan will

00:13:39.680 --> 00:13:45.920
[Amit Varma]: know on my writing group, which we are part of the WhatsApp group, I mentioned an author yesterday.

00:13:45.920 --> 00:13:51.200
[Amit Varma]: And I said that, okay, you know, he's a good guy. I like his work. But two years back, he exploded

00:13:51.200 --> 00:13:57.200
[Amit Varma]: at me on social media for something I did, but I couldn't remember why. So I was like, theek hai jaane do, abhi yaad nahi hai, kuch hua hoga.

00:13:57.200 --> 00:13:58.640
[Guest 2]: Exactly, toh khush hai na tu.

00:13:58.640 --> 00:14:05.360
[Amit Varma]: Main toh khush hoon. So to kind of get back to you. So, you know, tell me about your childhood, where did you grow up? Tell me about your mom?

00:14:06.800 --> 00:14:11.440
[Guest 2]: Yeah, so as I said that I don't remember much, but whatever I remember, I'll tell you that

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:17.520
[Guest 2]: I was a service officer's kid. My dad was in the Air Force. And I remember most of the postings,

00:14:17.520 --> 00:14:23.760
[Guest 2]: we were in Bareilly and Jamnagar. And then the best posting we ever had was the National Defense

00:14:23.760 --> 00:14:30.320
[Guest 2]: Academy. And that's where I realized that I do not want to join the armed forces because it was a

00:14:30.320 --> 00:14:35.600
[Guest 2]: beautiful resort, but you don't want to be part of it from the active level. And service officers

00:14:35.600 --> 00:14:41.680
[Guest 2]: children have always two options, right? Either you get inspired ki hamare pardada bhi army mein hua karte the types

00:14:41.680 --> 00:14:47.520
[Guest 2]: or second is bhai apne bas ki baat nahi hai. And that happened to me in the National Defense Academy.

00:14:47.520 --> 00:14:53.360
[Guest 2]: My dad was, you know, we were on a scooter and the NDA cadets while they are, you know,

00:14:53.360 --> 00:14:56.320
[Guest 2]: going on a cycle next to you, if they see a senior officer or

00:14:58.320 --> 00:15:03.360
[Guest 2]: wife, you're supposed to stretch your arms like this on the cycle, which means that respect diya

00:15:03.360 --> 00:15:10.320
[Guest 2]: aapko. Toh we were there and my dad's coursemate, he was also driving and then suddenly he realized

00:15:10.320 --> 00:15:15.360
[Guest 2]: that this yeh cadet ne aise haath nahi kiya tha, stretch nahi kiya tha. And he stopped the cadet

00:15:15.360 --> 00:15:18.880
[Guest 2]: and asked him, what's your name? So I don't remember the cadet's name. So it's say, for example,

00:15:18.880 --> 00:15:26.800
[Guest 2]: Roshan Abbas. So R-O-S-H aise front roll sabke saamne karnega. And that when I saw, I realized

00:15:26.800 --> 00:15:32.480
[Guest 2]: bhai, my dad would start doing this at home. So I'm not going to join the National Defense Academy,

00:15:32.480 --> 00:15:37.600
[Guest 2]: but the good news was because you are an Air Force officer's son, you play golf at a young age,

00:15:37.600 --> 00:15:42.240
[Guest 2]: you get exposed to, there's so many cricket grounds there, football grounds. So my love

00:15:42.240 --> 00:15:47.600
[Guest 2]: for sports started at the National Defense Academy. The good news was that some 25 years later,

00:15:47.600 --> 00:15:52.720
[Guest 2]: I performed for the 117th course there. And I told my father, without doing all this effort,

00:15:52.720 --> 00:15:57.440
[Guest 2]: see, I'm addressing the entire academy in front of the admiral of the Indian Navy.

00:15:57.440 --> 00:16:02.800
[Guest 2]: So that's how my childhood was going from one Air Force station to the other. And then one fine day,

00:16:02.800 --> 00:16:09.200
[Guest 2]: my parents said ki yaar isko thoda stabilize karke. So we came to Pune. Now, Pune at that

00:16:09.200 --> 00:16:14.640
[Guest 2]: point of time was, means, you know, Gokhale, Ranade, Agarkar, that was the background and

00:16:14.640 --> 00:16:20.160
[Guest 2]: Gokhale Institute. I know Amit had an interface with that institute. So it was an amazing

00:16:20.160 --> 00:16:27.680
[Guest 2]: cosmopolitan world in the armed forces to hardcore Puneri. And I loved it because in the armed

00:16:27.680 --> 00:16:33.680
[Guest 2]: forces, you're not exposed to art in that form, right? Everybody, NDA cadets also do a great job

00:16:33.680 --> 00:16:38.880
[Guest 2]: when it comes to theater, music and all of that. But when I came to Pune, I realized that there was

00:16:38.880 --> 00:16:44.320
[Guest 2]: this new world, which I loved, which is, you know, getting exposed to going for Sawai Gandharva at

00:16:44.320 --> 00:16:48.240
[Guest 2]: six in the morning. And my mother shifted with me to make sure my education was good. So I

00:16:48.240 --> 00:16:54.320
[Guest 2]: was in Karnataka High School. I got introduced to Pula Deshpande, who I believe is the greatest

00:16:54.320 --> 00:17:00.640
[Guest 2]: living legend across the world because nobody is an actor, writer, director, harmonium player,

00:17:00.640 --> 00:17:09.600
[Guest 2]: music composer, plus Ran Doordarshan for such a long time and an orator. It's a disrespect to

00:17:09.600 --> 00:17:15.600
[Guest 2]: call him a comedian. So from that perspective, Indian classical music and my introduction to

00:17:15.600 --> 00:17:20.720
[Guest 2]: cricket, I started playing at PYC. And that's where I realized that I had a lot of cricket in

00:17:20.720 --> 00:17:26.560
[Guest 2]: me mentally, but not physically, because that was the generation of Sachin Tendulkar, unfortunately

00:17:26.560 --> 00:17:30.400
[Guest 2]: for us. And that's the reason I wrote this book, How Sachin Destroyed My Life, which we'll talk

00:17:30.400 --> 00:17:35.120
[Guest 2]: about it later. And I started playing and I realized that I had a good hand-eye coordination.

00:17:35.120 --> 00:17:42.800
[Guest 2]: I was doing well. The music was going well. I started playing the tabla. So then once I settled

00:17:42.800 --> 00:17:48.160
[Guest 2]: in Pune, I got exposed to this world and I was in Narayan Ped, hardcore Peshwa territory,

00:17:48.160 --> 00:17:56.800
[Guest 2]: where music and arts was flowing. Experimental theater was in a big way there. And then

00:17:58.160 --> 00:18:01.120
[Guest 2]: post that, I joined Ferguson College where I met Amit Verma.

00:18:01.120 --> 00:18:03.760
[Guest 1]: That's what I was going to say. I said, Ferguson must have been a common thing for you guys.

00:18:05.280 --> 00:18:07.360
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, the weird thing is, I don't think we knew each other.

00:18:08.880 --> 00:18:13.280
[Amit Varma]: It's only later when we were both working in MTV in the late 90s, 97, 98,

00:18:13.280 --> 00:18:16.880
[Amit Varma]: that we realized that, hey, we are both from Ferguson and we had common friends and all of

00:18:16.880 --> 00:18:25.520
[Amit Varma]: that, whom I'm sure he's forgotten. He was like, okay. So we actually became friends then. So it's

00:18:25.520 --> 00:18:29.680
[Amit Varma]: kind of weird. You know, so I can technically call him a college friend, but we didn't know

00:18:29.680 --> 00:18:34.080
[Guest 1]: each other in college. My only theory on that would be that you were, as you keep saying,

00:18:34.080 --> 00:18:38.000
[Guest 1]: you're an introvert. So you did what to meet new people. And Sathe was too lazy to meet anyone.

00:18:39.440 --> 00:18:44.400
[Guest 2]: No, but you know, I remember him because there was this group of guys who used to play chess

00:18:44.400 --> 00:18:49.440
[Guest 2]: just near the Ferguson canteen. Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah. So behind the gym building. Yeah,

00:18:49.440 --> 00:18:53.440
[Guest 2]: behind the gym building. And I used to see these guys and say, every day they play chess. And he

00:18:53.440 --> 00:18:58.240
[Guest 2]: was a good chess player. And I was a college captain and played for Maharashtra and all of that.

00:18:59.040 --> 00:19:06.960
[Guest 2]: So I was told that these guys are great. So say hello to them. If you get a chance, do it.

00:19:06.960 --> 00:19:13.520
[Guest 2]: So that's why I remember Amit very well. And I think, did you ever go to the National Film

00:19:13.520 --> 00:19:18.560
[Guest 2]: Archives, NFAI at some point? I would have gone there to see films. My dad was director of the

00:19:18.560 --> 00:19:23.920
[Guest 2]: FTII. But I would go for the film festivals at NFAI. I think I met you there once. Possible.

00:19:23.920 --> 00:19:28.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. See, I also forget everything. It's a tiny secret. People ask me,

00:19:28.560 --> 00:19:33.280
[Amit Varma]: how is your retention? And I have to tell them that boss, there is a lot of research.

00:19:33.280 --> 00:19:37.200
[Amit Varma]: I do all my research one day before the episodes. I don't remember anything after that.

00:19:37.200 --> 00:19:40.960
[Guest 1]: So like, I have a strange feeling that slowly this episode is going to become

00:19:40.960 --> 00:19:48.960
[Amit Varma]: like Karan Arjun. And you mentioned golf. And I remember like one of my past guests,

00:19:48.960 --> 00:19:52.240
[Amit Varma]: Subrat Mohanty, he was in town, I was hanging out with him. So he told me,

00:19:52.240 --> 00:19:57.360
[Amit Varma]: you know, the mantra which bankers go by, which is a 963 formula. Have you heard it?

00:19:57.360 --> 00:20:02.960
[Amit Varma]: No. So the 963 formula is, let me see, I don't want to get it wrong. Yeah. Lend at 9%,

00:20:02.960 --> 00:20:12.720
[Amit Varma]: borrow at 6%, golf at 3 o'clock. Since you mentioned golf, and I just realized that Roshan

00:20:12.720 --> 00:20:18.480
[Amit Varma]: a little while earlier spoke about how if you get interested in something, time expands to fill the

00:20:18.480 --> 00:20:23.120
[Amit Varma]: work available. And that's actually where it originates from is Parkinson's law,

00:20:23.120 --> 00:20:28.240
[Amit Varma]: is that work expands to fill the time available, which is kind of how I've lived my life. Like,

00:20:28.240 --> 00:20:33.520
[Amit Varma]: even if I have one thing to do in a day, it will take the whole damn day. So it's, you know, us,

00:20:34.160 --> 00:20:40.080
[Amit Varma]: lazy buggers. So tell me a bit more about, you know, Vikram, what you wanted to,

00:20:40.080 --> 00:20:45.360
[Amit Varma]: like, when you were going through life like that, you're in a very cultural environment. So you're

00:20:45.360 --> 00:20:49.920
[Amit Varma]: both playing tabla. And I presume singing because you do sing quite well. And you will sing for us

00:20:49.920 --> 00:20:55.520
[Amit Varma]: later on the show. And you're also into cricket, and you're kind of picking that up. So at this

00:20:55.520 --> 00:20:59.840
[Amit Varma]: point, you know, what did you think of yourself doing? What was your sort of conception of

00:20:59.840 --> 00:21:07.360
[Guest 2]: yourself? So that is the problem, right? I had no conception of anything up until today. So

00:21:07.360 --> 00:21:12.720
[Guest 2]: the thing was that my mom was saying that, you know, tabla, keep, you know, and today in my

00:21:12.720 --> 00:21:16.800
[Guest 2]: motivational talks, I talk about the fact that you have to be consistent and blah, blah, blah,

00:21:16.800 --> 00:21:21.840
[Guest 2]: this exactly. So whatever I speak today is not something I did. And that is the reason I have a

00:21:21.840 --> 00:21:26.320
[Guest 2]: gravity of the situation. And I remember having this conversation with Sanjay Manjrekar. And he

00:21:26.320 --> 00:21:31.120
[Guest 2]: said that one of the reasons I can probably analyze the game better is because I was not

00:21:31.120 --> 00:21:37.200
[Guest 2]: good enough. And I think he did not say it in these words, but this is what I interpreted,

00:21:37.200 --> 00:21:42.240
[Guest 2]: because this was a conversation I had with him about Sachin Tendulkar. And he said that many a

00:21:42.240 --> 00:21:48.720
[Guest 2]: time Sachin Tendulkar did not realize that he was too good to know that there are other people who

00:21:48.720 --> 00:21:53.440
[Guest 2]: may not be as good enough. And therefore you have to plan for them as well. And I realized that my

00:21:53.440 --> 00:21:59.200
[Guest 2]: understanding of the environment was better from probably a writer's perspective is because I could

00:21:59.200 --> 00:22:05.280
[Guest 2]: not play the on drive as good as the other guy. Sometimes as artists, as sports people, we do

00:22:05.280 --> 00:22:09.120
[Guest 2]: things naturally. And this is a conversation again with Sachin Tendulkar. And I asked him that,

00:22:09.120 --> 00:22:14.400
[Guest 2]: how did you motivate yourself? And he looked at me like, are you even crazy? Are you crazy?

00:22:14.400 --> 00:22:19.440
[Guest 2]: What is motivation? So I said that, you know, you have to push yourself to do. He said, never.

00:22:20.080 --> 00:22:24.160
[Unknown]: If you like something, why would you like to, why would you want to push? Now he doesn't realize

00:22:24.160 --> 00:22:30.000
[Guest 2]: that nine out of 10 people on a bad day require some kind of an external stimulus to go and do

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:36.320
[Guest 2]: what they, even if they like that activity. So for me, I realized that, you know, I was liking this,

00:22:36.320 --> 00:22:41.440
[Guest 2]: but there was not that intrinsic desire of putting eight hours. That is the laziness factor that

00:22:41.440 --> 00:22:47.040
[Guest 2]: Roshan talked about. But that process of going to Sawai Gandharvan, listening to Pandit Bhimsen Joshi

00:22:47.040 --> 00:22:53.840
[Guest 2]: at 6am, that gave me joy. And I thought, I have to stay in this. I have to stay in this joy.

00:22:53.840 --> 00:22:59.280
[Guest 2]: This doesn't mean that I have to become Pandit Bhimsen Joshi. Now that is something I realized

00:22:59.280 --> 00:23:04.000
[Guest 2]: that this excellence of excellence is fine, but I don't have to do it. But whoever has excellence,

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:09.600
[Guest 2]: if he goes there and stays in the pond, and that is the only reason after Ferguson College, when

00:23:09.600 --> 00:23:14.720
[Guest 2]: we had no idea about, you know, post-grad, what to do, I was playing cricket. I realized that,

00:23:14.720 --> 00:23:19.440
[Guest 2]: you know, my coach had told me that you've got to get at least 300 in that season to even

00:23:19.440 --> 00:23:23.760
[Guest 2]: come to a point where you will compete with the Mumbai guys, because the Mumbai guys were making

00:23:23.760 --> 00:23:29.120
[Guest 2]: 2-2,000 runs a season. Even Maharashtra had a fabulous team at that point of time in Ranji

00:23:29.120 --> 00:23:34.160
[Guest 2]: Trophy. So then I realized that, boss, this is not good enough, so I will have to prepare for MBA,

00:23:34.160 --> 00:23:39.840
[Guest 2]: because MBA was graduation by that time. You will get a job worth 8-10,000.

00:23:39.840 --> 00:23:45.840
[Guest 2]: And thankfully, I had a good set of friends, and I always believe that, boss, 5 business relationships

00:23:45.840 --> 00:23:50.800
[Guest 2]: and 5 friends is what you need to survive in life, because you don't have a bandwidth on this.

00:23:50.800 --> 00:23:56.560
[Guest 2]: I don't have it. After that, you have acquaintances, whom you develop for business, that yes,

00:23:56.560 --> 00:24:01.600
[Guest 2]: I will get business from this. But 5 friends and 5 business, and I believe that also has Pareto's

00:24:01.600 --> 00:24:06.560
[Guest 2]: principle. If you look back at Roshan's career, probably there are 5 clients that made his last

00:24:06.560 --> 00:24:11.360
[Guest 2]: company, Encompass. There were a lot of small companies which kind of propelled the 50 lakh,

00:24:11.360 --> 00:24:15.840
[Guest 2]: whatever, small small business, but the big guys like what? The Asian Pay. The Asian Pay. Amit

00:24:15.840 --> 00:24:21.360
[Guest 2]: Singles. Amit Singles of the world, exactly. And that applies to life as well, that those 5

00:24:21.360 --> 00:24:27.280
[Guest 2]: relationships, if you develop all your life in business and in this thing, and this is something

00:24:27.280 --> 00:24:32.640
[Guest 2]: that I kept with. And I said that these are my 4-5 friends, this is what we have to do, we have to

00:24:32.640 --> 00:24:38.960
[Guest 2]: stay in the zone, that boss, I like cricket. And then, that is where I think I interacted with

00:24:38.960 --> 00:24:43.440
[Guest 2]: Harsha Bhokle for the first time. And I said that yeah, this is an interesting space. Again, not

00:24:43.440 --> 00:24:47.920
[Guest 2]: because I want to become a commentator and all, but this is a good space. So I was always looking

00:24:47.920 --> 00:24:52.880
[Guest 2]: at spaces, that I want to swim in this pond, I want to swim in this pond, I want to become one or not,

00:24:52.880 --> 00:24:58.240
[Guest 2]: I didn't know, because as I said, I was living those moments at that time. And then my friends

00:24:58.240 --> 00:25:03.120
[Guest 2]: gathered together and said that, you know, see again those 5 friends came to me and said,

00:25:03.120 --> 00:25:10.000
[Guest 2]: let's study from you, you crack the MBA entrance exam later. You will not believe, there was the

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:14.160
[Guest 2]: MBA entrance exam and I was not motivated to go for the exam, because I didn't know what I will

00:25:14.160 --> 00:25:18.880
[Guest 2]: do with finance and marketing and sales. There were guys who came to my house, picked me up,

00:25:18.880 --> 00:25:22.800
[Guest 2]: took me to the place where the, you know, they had taken my study, you know, I had taken all the

00:25:22.800 --> 00:25:28.800
[Guest 2]: preparation for 15 days. And one of these guys, Sunil Fatak, who is now in the Bay Area, he knew

00:25:28.800 --> 00:25:34.880
[Guest 2]: the system inside out, which questions will come. So he told me that also and I got my MBA entrance

00:25:34.880 --> 00:25:42.320
[Guest 2]: and it was a premier college. So then I had to do my MBA. There was no option. But by that time,

00:25:42.320 --> 00:25:49.680
[Guest 2]: I realized that media is probably a space I need to go to. And thankfully, all these friends,

00:25:49.680 --> 00:25:53.840
[Guest 2]: my cricket friends gathered and said, okay, you know, we will find a way out somewhere

00:25:53.840 --> 00:25:59.840
[Guest 2]: to get a career. And guess what, I had done BSc in Geology. You did a BSc in Geology? Yeah,

00:25:59.840 --> 00:26:04.640
[Guest 2]: before that, because what happened was after 12th, everybody was engineering, engineering,

00:26:04.640 --> 00:26:10.080
[Guest 2]: so I applied for polymer engineering. And again, my mamaji, this is a funny story, my mama came to

00:26:10.080 --> 00:26:16.400
[Guest 2]: me and said that, you know, I don't think it's a good idea, because I have repented. I don't want

00:26:16.400 --> 00:26:24.400
[Guest 2]: you to repent. So, and I love my mamaji because he was the one who said that, boss, don't do anything.

00:26:24.400 --> 00:26:28.400
[Guest 2]: Everybody in the family, intellectually oriented, you should do this, you should do that,

00:26:28.400 --> 00:26:38.480
[Guest 2]: up the benchmark. I didn't have that concept. So the story is that in BSc, I got 5 out of 100

00:26:38.480 --> 00:26:44.160
[Guest 2]: in Chemistry. So there was a parent-teacher meeting and my mamaji went to meet the chemistry

00:26:44.160 --> 00:26:50.400
[Guest 2]: professor. And I was like, I was really scared, what will he come and stuff like that. I was

00:26:50.400 --> 00:26:54.800
[Guest 2]: outside waiting, what will happen, what will happen, what will happen. And I lied to them

00:26:54.800 --> 00:27:00.000
[Guest 2]: saying that my parents are out of town. And I told mama that please go on behalf of the parents. So

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:05.120
[Guest 2]: he had also said, okay, I will handle this. And he came out of that parent-teacher meeting,

00:27:05.120 --> 00:27:10.960
[Guest 2]: and he hugged me. So I said, why is he hugging me 5 out of 100, it's embarrassing. He said,

00:27:10.960 --> 00:27:20.080
[Guest 2]: the one before you had 3 out of 100. I'm proud of you. So that is the relationship I had with my

00:27:20.080 --> 00:27:24.000
[Guest 1]: mama. You know, I think in every family, there is a person like this. Yeah. You know,

00:27:25.120 --> 00:27:30.560
[Guest 1]: one set of overachievers, one who is living life. No, no, because he must have suffered.

00:27:30.560 --> 00:27:35.600
[Guest 1]: That's what I'm saying. He sees that another one is dying. Yeah, that's what I was thinking. In

00:27:35.600 --> 00:27:41.600
[Guest 2]: every family, there is one of these. Relax, chill, life will be fine. Exactly. So he, I mean,

00:27:41.600 --> 00:27:46.720
[Guest 2]: to complete the story, he told me not to do engineering. But then there was a balance,

00:27:46.720 --> 00:27:52.880
[Guest 2]: you had to satisfy people at home. So it can't be arts, it can't be commerce, it has to be science.

00:27:53.520 --> 00:27:59.360
[Guest 2]: So there was BSc, which is the most disastrous course in the history of mankind. Because you

00:27:59.360 --> 00:28:05.520
[Guest 2]: neither here nor there. You don't have the capacity for R&D. So basically, you have to do BSc. Then

00:28:05.520 --> 00:28:12.160
[Guest 2]: in BSc, physics, chemistry, the problem was nothing mattered. So can't study matter.

00:28:15.760 --> 00:28:21.200
[Guest 2]: So then geology is now, when I look back, geology was a very interesting subject. But at that time,

00:28:21.200 --> 00:28:28.320
[Guest 2]: what to see inside the rock, inside the mineral, but finally I did that. And I remember my

00:28:28.320 --> 00:28:32.560
[Guest 2]: grandmother introducing me, typical Marathi family people coming home and said,

00:28:36.800 --> 00:28:39.440
[Guest 2]: what has your grandson? Ordinary BSc.

00:28:43.200 --> 00:28:50.480
[Guest 2]: How can you introduce me? Ordinary. Ordinary BSc. For her, it meant that his career is over,

00:28:50.480 --> 00:28:56.800
[Guest 2]: he has done ordinary BSc. And there was this look on her face that it's over. So in Pune,

00:28:56.800 --> 00:29:03.360
[Guest 2]: you could not have done BSc, it was a complete failure. But thankfully, in that process, I

00:29:03.360 --> 00:29:10.720
[Guest 2]: realized that even with MBA, I should not be doing the standard stuff. And that's why when I came to

00:29:10.720 --> 00:29:17.120
[Guest 2]: campus, I was one of the toppers and I did not get the companies that I wanted. Coke and Hindustan

00:29:17.120 --> 00:29:23.680
[Guest 2]: Lever at that point of time, my CV was shortlisted. And I decided I will go on my own.

00:29:23.680 --> 00:29:28.880
[Guest 2]: And guess what? I went to Mumbai in 1997. And I started a wrestling company.

00:29:31.920 --> 00:29:32.880
[Amit Varma]: News to both of us.

00:29:37.120 --> 00:29:43.040
[Guest 2]: When I got my MBA, Jerry Maguire was there and Mark McCormack.

00:29:45.680 --> 00:29:49.040
[Guest 2]: By that time, I had clarity that if there is an interface between management and sports,

00:29:49.040 --> 00:29:54.800
[Guest 2]: then what will happen? So obviously, watching the movie, I thought that this is a new problem,

00:29:54.800 --> 00:30:00.080
[Guest 2]: right? Everybody is watching English Premier League. And now every kid in urban India believes

00:30:00.080 --> 00:30:05.120
[Guest 2]: that he is going to take the football coach's job at Manchester United or Arsenal. And so I get a

00:30:05.120 --> 00:30:11.520
[Guest 2]: call every week from some friend's son who's saying, uncle, I want to be in football. So

00:30:11.520 --> 00:30:18.400
[Guest 2]: then suddenly I'll hear, why? You know, I want to do something because we lost. I said, who lost?

00:30:18.400 --> 00:30:25.680
[Guest 2]: Puddar College? No, he said, Arsenal. So look at the construct of patriotism now.

00:30:25.680 --> 00:30:30.080
[Guest 2]: Where does patriotism come from? You know, you play for your college. I played for PYC,

00:30:30.080 --> 00:30:35.200
[Guest 2]: I played for Ferguson, I was patriotic. Now this fellow in Ghatkopar is patriotic about Chelsea.

00:30:35.200 --> 00:30:39.840
[Guest 2]: And he wants to be the manager there. But that happened to me. That happened to me and I wanted

00:30:39.840 --> 00:30:46.000
[Guest 2]: to head IMG, Mark McCormack, because he, you know, ran all the businesses, business of sport.

00:30:46.640 --> 00:30:53.120
[Guest 2]: And that's what drove me to Mumbai. And that point of time Premchand Degra had become Mr. Universe.

00:30:54.160 --> 00:30:59.360
[Guest 2]: You know, not wrestling as such, but it was bodybuilding, which went to wrestling and

00:30:59.360 --> 00:31:03.680
[Guest 2]: Arnold Schwarzenegger's book I had read at that point of time, along with Dorian Yates,

00:31:03.680 --> 00:31:11.520
[Guest 2]: was the bodybuilder's supreme. And one of my friends came to me that, I want to bring Mr. Universe to Mumbai.

00:31:11.520 --> 00:31:18.160
[Guest 2]: I said, super idea. So then we contacted Mr. Universe, the franchisee, and they said that,

00:31:18.160 --> 00:31:23.120
[Guest 2]: you know, we look at you. So I met at that time, instead of doing your summer training or whatever,

00:31:23.120 --> 00:31:30.400
[Guest 2]: I met the Chief Minister of Maharashtra. And I told him that was Narayan Rane.

00:31:30.400 --> 00:31:34.720
[Guest 2]: I said, I want to bring Mr. Universe. He said, what do you want to bring?

00:31:36.400 --> 00:31:42.880
[Guest 2]: Bring him. As if I was getting some like, you know, some guy's invitation to come in a plane.

00:31:42.880 --> 00:31:49.280
[Guest 2]: But that kind of, you know, but that six months was very important because I realized at that time

00:31:49.280 --> 00:31:55.680
[Guest 2]: that the sports business is not to do with actually organizing sports. It was about television.

00:31:55.680 --> 00:32:01.280
[Guest 2]: And for me, it was important that, you know, to join television to understand the sporting business.

00:32:01.280 --> 00:32:08.080
[Guest 2]: And that's where, you know, we, the MTB offer happened. And I used to do summer training at,

00:32:08.080 --> 00:32:13.120
[Guest 2]: you know, a company called Plus Channel during my stint and which was owned by Mahesh Bhatt.

00:32:13.120 --> 00:32:20.480
[Guest 2]: And there I met… Mukesh Khanna? No, no. What was it? Amit… Amit Khanna. Amit Khanna, Mahesh Bhatt.

00:32:20.480 --> 00:32:26.960
[Guest 2]: Amit Khanna, Mahesh Bhatt. And there was this movie they had done called Papa Kehte Hain, whose soundtrack was excellent, actually.

00:32:39.680 --> 00:32:45.040
[Guest 2]: I was there at this recording. Oh, wow. Amazing. And then I said, man, this is an interesting area.

00:32:45.040 --> 00:32:51.200
[Guest 2]: Obviously, Bollywood regular exposure was there. But I said that this is an interesting area that

00:32:51.200 --> 00:32:56.880
[Guest 2]: I should probably look at in the future. And there was this American, Japanese boss who you know very

00:32:56.880 --> 00:33:05.760
[Amit Varma]: well, Niren Hiromi. He's a character. MTB marketing head. Legend. I remember a story that he was the

00:33:05.760 --> 00:33:12.240
[Guest 2]: one who taught me, you know, fundamentals of marketing. So what is an ad? Dude, headline,

00:33:12.240 --> 00:33:18.720
[Guest 2]: body copy, baseline, out. So he was teaching me this whole principle of advertising in the car

00:33:18.720 --> 00:33:24.160
[Guest 2]: one day. And we were going past Prabhadevi. And there was this creative guy also sitting, Pankaj,

00:33:24.160 --> 00:33:28.720
[Guest 2]: next to me. And he was saying, you know, this is how the logo should be. Dude, you got to get this

00:33:28.720 --> 00:33:35.920
[Guest 2]: right, this right. And suddenly we look outside and there is a Shiv Sena poster on the side,

00:33:35.920 --> 00:33:42.400
[Guest 2]: Prabhadevi's signal. There is Tiger and there is Bada Saheb Thackeray. He suddenly like, dude,

00:33:42.400 --> 00:33:52.000
[Guest 2]: who cleared that layout? And I was like, this guy is so funny. He actually got me into MTB.

00:33:53.680 --> 00:34:00.080
[Guest 2]: But before that, again, my love for Mark McCormack made me join professional management group. So

00:34:00.080 --> 00:34:05.200
[Guest 2]: what happened during the time when I was playing cricket, I had befriended Samir Dige. Samir Dige

00:34:05.200 --> 00:34:11.120
[Guest 2]: was then Mumbai captain and he played for Mumbai with Sachin and the whole amazing gang, Nilesh

00:34:11.120 --> 00:34:16.800
[Guest 2]: Kulkarni, Paras Mamre, Salil Ankola. The story that Salil Ankola, every time I meet him even

00:34:16.800 --> 00:34:22.160
[Guest 2]: today, I'm scared of him because a ball that was pitch short, I still have the bruise in my

00:34:23.760 --> 00:34:29.280
[Guest 2]: chest because he was very, very quick at that point of time, very strong lad. And yeah, so

00:34:29.280 --> 00:34:34.000
[Guest 2]: Samir Dige, I knew and I called him and I said that, you know, I started this company and all.

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:39.760
[Guest 2]: And I don't know what to do, but I want to be in cricket. So he introduced me to Hemant Kinkre.

00:34:39.760 --> 00:34:45.360
[Guest 2]: Hemant Kinkre is Sunil Gavaskar's cousin. And he was earlier married to Asha Bhusle's daughter.

00:34:45.360 --> 00:34:52.240
[Guest 2]: Fabulous cricketer, good batsman for CCI. He said that, you know, I'll introduce you to Mr. Gavaskar

00:34:52.240 --> 00:34:56.640
[Guest 2]: and Sumedh Shah, who ran professional management group, which was the only company at that point

00:34:56.640 --> 00:35:02.240
[Guest 2]: of time, which kind of resembled, you know, this cricketing world and management kind of a world.

00:35:02.240 --> 00:35:08.000
[Guest 2]: I met Harsha that time and I met Harsha and told him that, you know, I want to be in this space.

00:35:08.000 --> 00:35:13.440
[Guest 2]: He said, you work in PMG. I also worked there years back. So you'll get some basic exposure there.

00:35:14.400 --> 00:35:21.440
[Guest 2]: But it was a year's stint with that's where I started imitating Sunil Gavaskar. And, you know,

00:35:21.440 --> 00:35:26.080
[Guest 2]: I used to do this in front of Vaishali Hotel. I don't know, Amit will not remember that I used

00:35:26.080 --> 00:35:33.200
[Guest 2]: to gather a crowd imitating cricketers. And that is where that theater, music, cricket all came

00:35:33.200 --> 00:35:38.160
[Guest 1]: together. And you're still at MTV at this time? No, no, no, I have not joined MTV yet. Oh my God.

00:35:38.160 --> 00:35:44.080
[Guest 2]: So this is a stint before? This is a stint before just 8 to 10 months trying to see whether the

00:35:44.080 --> 00:35:48.560
[Guest 2]: sports business really exists. And I realized that there is no sports business in India.

00:35:48.560 --> 00:35:52.960
[Guest 2]: I think the sports business in India started after IPL. Till that time, it was only BCCI.

00:35:52.960 --> 00:35:56.640
[Guest 2]: There is no business. BCCI tells you what to do, you do. If you call it business,

00:35:56.640 --> 00:36:01.760
[Guest 2]: then it's good for you. Otherwise, there's nothing else. Then I worked with Mr. Gavaskar

00:36:01.760 --> 00:36:06.640
[Guest 2]: and I realized that there is nothing here. And television is what I need to do. That's

00:36:06.640 --> 00:36:11.360
[Guest 1]: what brought me to music television. Did you get Mr. Universe?

00:36:11.360 --> 00:36:18.320
[Guest 2]: No, because it was a wrong idea.

00:36:19.680 --> 00:36:24.560
[Amit Varma]: So a couple of things I want to sort of double click on before we continue with the chronology.

00:36:24.560 --> 00:36:30.160
[Amit Varma]: And one of them is very interesting where you, you know, you speak about how when you were playing

00:36:30.160 --> 00:36:34.480
[Amit Varma]: cricket, it was obvious to you that you're not, you know, going to be at that level. And I remember,

00:36:34.480 --> 00:36:39.680
[Amit Varma]: I retired from chess as a 19 year old in the early 90s, when I kind of came to the same

00:36:39.680 --> 00:36:46.080
[Amit Varma]: realization. So, you know, what is the point? And also in the particular club where I played,

00:36:46.080 --> 00:36:50.480
[Amit Varma]: which was a fatke club in Pune in the early 90s, there were these couple of kids who were really

00:36:50.480 --> 00:36:54.640
[Amit Varma]: good, much better than me. So I thought, okay, kids here are beating me, what's the chance outside?

00:36:54.640 --> 00:36:58.640
[Amit Varma]: Then one became a grandmaster, one became a master. So, you know, I shouldn't have been

00:36:58.640 --> 00:37:04.160
[Amit Varma]: too hard on myself. But the thing here is that in sport, you know, when you're not good,

00:37:04.160 --> 00:37:10.720
[Amit Varma]: because you're getting that instant feedback, ki, you know, Salil Ankula ne bol ki, ribs pe laga,

00:37:10.720 --> 00:37:17.120
[Amit Varma]: abhi, you know, I can't walk properly for two days. But in art, that feedback loop isn't there.

00:37:17.120 --> 00:37:21.680
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, what happens is that a lot of people who get into the arts, whether they are

00:37:21.680 --> 00:37:25.520
[Amit Varma]: singing or writing or whatever, they think they are much better than they are. Now, there are two

00:37:25.520 --> 00:37:29.680
[Amit Varma]: sides to this. And the negative side is you can waste a lot of time doing something you're not

00:37:29.680 --> 00:37:34.960
[Amit Varma]: cut out for, because you don't have the self awareness. But the positive side is that you

00:37:34.960 --> 00:37:38.640
[Amit Varma]: don't know that you suck, because everybody sucks at the start, whenever they do something,

00:37:38.640 --> 00:37:44.720
[Amit Varma]: you don't know that you suck. So you continue. And just the sheer hard work that you then put in

00:37:44.720 --> 00:37:49.040
[Amit Varma]: and the sheer repetition actually makes you good at it. Basically, you fake it till you make it.

00:37:49.040 --> 00:37:53.680
[Amit Varma]: Like when I think of myself as a writer in my 20s, my writing was shit, and I didn't have the

00:37:53.680 --> 00:37:59.680
[Amit Varma]: judgment to know it. So you know, I, you know, I wrote bad things, I thought I was a cat's whiskers.

00:37:59.680 --> 00:38:04.080
[Amit Varma]: But it's a good thing because I you know, that self delusion just kind of keeps you going.

00:38:04.080 --> 00:38:10.240
[Amit Varma]: So these seem to me to be two very different ways in which it plays out that in sport,

00:38:10.240 --> 00:38:16.000
[Amit Varma]: you know exactly where you are. And you know, the work you need to do to get ahead. And that's got

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:20.320
[Amit Varma]: his good and bad aspects. And the good aspect of that is you can work hard and get there.

00:38:20.320 --> 00:38:24.400
[Amit Varma]: And the bad aspect of that is that you can get disheartened, maybe you could have been something

00:38:24.400 --> 00:38:28.720
[Amit Varma]: good, but you don't put in the work. Whereas in the arts, again, there's the same thing,

00:38:28.720 --> 00:38:32.400
[Amit Varma]: you don't know that feedback loop is in there. And it can work in both good and bad ways.

00:38:32.400 --> 00:38:38.000
[Guest 2]: I think it's a very important point that in sport, the metric is very clear. It's runs,

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:45.040
[Guest 2]: it's what you see, right. And in that under 15 game in Mumbai, when I saw Tendulkar play,

00:38:45.040 --> 00:38:52.240
[Guest 2]: when I saw Vinod play, and while we were grafting, you know, scoring, say 25 runs in 40 balls, and

00:38:52.240 --> 00:38:58.960
[Guest 2]: we thought the conditions were difficult. And here was a guy who had scored 120 not out in the first,

00:38:58.960 --> 00:39:03.840
[Guest 2]: you know, first one or one and a half, two hours, and he left that match and went to Thane and

00:39:03.840 --> 00:39:10.080
[Guest 2]: scored another 100 runs. So the benchmark was like, so high, that you were like, you're not

00:39:10.080 --> 00:39:15.520
[Guest 2]: even in the play 11, boss, you should not be playing this game. So the metric is very, very

00:39:15.520 --> 00:39:20.320
[Guest 2]: clear. In art, there is a very complex problem, right? Because art, you don't know what the

00:39:20.320 --> 00:39:26.720
[Guest 2]: metric is, you also work on conviction. And everybody tells you that, boss, like, you know,

00:39:26.720 --> 00:39:31.840
[Guest 2]: as a filmmaker, also Roshan would tell you that many a times I've seen and I worked in the movie

00:39:31.840 --> 00:39:37.920
[Guest 2]: industry for a couple of years as well, that what is the line where you say, boss, mere creative ko

00:39:37.920 --> 00:39:44.080
[Guest 2]: as a director, I trust. But people are telling you that your script is faulty. But no, you have to

00:39:44.080 --> 00:39:49.200
[Guest 2]: take a call. Should you listen to the person because they say the script is faulty, or because

00:39:49.200 --> 00:39:54.160
[Guest 2]: you've been also told that a creator has to have conviction in doing your creative work. This is

00:39:54.160 --> 00:39:59.440
[Guest 1]: where the problem arises. No, I have a slight disagreement on this, which is the fact of saying

00:39:59.440 --> 00:40:03.600
[Guest 1]: that, you know, when you when you work in the creative and saying that, you know, you don't

00:40:03.600 --> 00:40:08.800
[Guest 1]: know whether you're good or you're bad or whatever, not true. What happens is, if you make your art

00:40:08.800 --> 00:40:14.640
[Guest 1]: incestuous, if you only listen to either yourself or a few people who may be yes or yes people

00:40:14.640 --> 00:40:19.760
[Guest 1]: around you, you're, you know, you can be in that loop of never knowing how you are. But if you put

00:40:19.760 --> 00:40:25.280
[Guest 1]: your art to test, I can be using my cricket bat sitting inside my room and constantly practicing,

00:40:25.280 --> 00:40:29.520
[Guest 1]: you know, what some stroke or the other, but till I don't go out and actually do it, you will never

00:40:29.520 --> 00:40:34.320
[Guest 1]: get to know. In art, I mean, and personally, I'll tell you this, that when I moved from Lucknow to

00:40:34.320 --> 00:40:39.120
[Guest 1]: Delhi, and when I first went out and said, I can think I'm a great debater, or I can take part in

00:40:39.120 --> 00:40:43.520
[Guest 1]: the debate. If I lose every debate in the world, then obviously I'm not a good debater. I can get

00:40:43.520 --> 00:40:48.000
[Guest 1]: on to radio, which is what I did next or whatever and stuff. And, you know, if I'm not moved into

00:40:48.000 --> 00:40:53.600
[Guest 1]: A grade recording artist within three months, so, you know, I actually always set these little

00:40:53.600 --> 00:40:57.920
[Guest 1]: targets for myself. Okay, boss, now this TV anchoring is going on. I remember at that time

00:40:57.920 --> 00:41:02.560
[Guest 1]: with Oprah, there used to be this other, there was this male, Phil Donahue. And Donahue used to do an

00:41:02.560 --> 00:41:07.760
[Guest 1]: interview. And one of Donahue's articles turned and said that a great career if you're on TV,

00:41:07.760 --> 00:41:13.360
[Guest 1]: is that if you're lucky, you'll get 10 years. If you're great, you might get so if you're lucky,

00:41:13.360 --> 00:41:16.640
[Guest 1]: you'll get five, if you're great, you'll get 10. And if you're God, you might end up getting more.

00:41:17.200 --> 00:41:21.520
[Guest 1]: So, you know, so immediately when I 25, I did television, I said, boss, 35, but this ain't

00:41:21.520 --> 00:41:29.200
[Guest 1]: going to end. It might not be God, but I'll manage. So I said 10 years. So I said that as a target,

00:41:29.200 --> 00:41:33.520
[Guest 1]: you know, and I sometimes feel this that if you don't, I was at Edinburgh, you know, in August,

00:41:34.160 --> 00:41:38.720
[Guest 1]: you're not just doing your show, you're on the road selling your show, you're standing out there

00:41:38.720 --> 00:41:42.800
[Guest 1]: every day and saying, come see my show, come see my show and the number of people who come to your

00:41:42.800 --> 00:41:48.960
[Guest 1]: show, then are the people who will go and tell the next set of people. So, you know, the problem is

00:41:48.960 --> 00:41:53.600
[Guest 1]: this that very often when you get incestuous about, I remember Public Demand was a show I used to do,

00:41:53.600 --> 00:41:57.120
[Guest 1]: I used to go out on the road, shoot every day and whatever. One day we got lazy.

00:41:57.120 --> 00:42:00.880
[Guest 1]: We had a segment left. And because we used to be produced by TV18 in those days,

00:42:00.880 --> 00:42:04.720
[Guest 1]: there were a bunch of TV18 interns standing outside. So the cameraman and my director said,

00:42:04.720 --> 00:42:08.480
[Guest 1]: let's shoot here. And we shot with all of those people, got fabulous bites.

00:42:09.200 --> 00:42:13.600
[Guest 1]: And it went into the episode. Raghav Bahl, who was the head of TV18, along with Rishi,

00:42:13.600 --> 00:42:18.320
[Guest 1]: was the creative director, used to put up these things on the wall as a review. And I still

00:42:18.320 --> 00:42:23.120
[Guest 1]: remember he put up this review and he said, I saw the latest episode of Public Demand, love this,

00:42:23.120 --> 00:42:28.240
[Guest 1]: this, this, this. And by the way, that last segment is being shot with our people. If you

00:42:28.240 --> 00:42:33.280
[Guest 1]: become so incestuous with your production, you will, if it is meant to be Public Demand, where's

00:42:33.280 --> 00:42:42.480
[Guest 1]: the public? You know, and it really struck home for me saying that if you don't keep testing that

00:42:42.480 --> 00:42:48.960
[Guest 1]: boundary, I worked with Vikram for years on end, right? I have seen him test that boundary. The

00:42:48.960 --> 00:42:54.000
[Guest 1]: first time it was just an impression of X, then it became X plus Y. Then he heard a bunch of us

00:42:54.000 --> 00:42:58.800
[Guest 1]: doing singing act. He never used to do a singing act before. He heard it and he said, I can do better

00:42:58.800 --> 00:43:02.800
[Guest 1]: than you. And he added that. Then he saw there was, you know, I mean, I've actually tracked him

00:43:02.800 --> 00:43:06.960
[Guest 1]: through this all because I've done it so well. But I've seen him do that. He's challenged every

00:43:06.960 --> 00:43:12.480
[Guest 1]: boundary, tested it, whatever didn't work, he dropped it. You're conscious of your art. You know,

00:43:12.480 --> 00:43:18.240
[Guest 1]: this conceit of art that happens sometimes, you get stuck in that. So I keep saying, my only

00:43:18.240 --> 00:43:22.960
[Guest 1]: thing is, I'm saying, whatever you do, keep testing. If you were not able to make money from the

00:43:22.960 --> 00:43:26.880
[Guest 1]: podcast today, Amit, with all the circles you created around it, at some point in time, you

00:43:26.880 --> 00:43:32.640
[Guest 1]: turn and say, either I'm doing it for myself or I'll leave it. But in this, Roshan, there are two

00:43:32.640 --> 00:43:38.800
[Guest 2]: kinds of situations. One is in the short term, like what happens in performing art, you get a

00:43:38.800 --> 00:43:44.720
[Guest 2]: metric. In stand-up comedy, performing art, you get a metric. If someone doesn't laugh in an art show,

00:43:44.720 --> 00:43:50.720
[Guest 2]: then you know that you're not good enough or you have to up the game. But in long-form art,

00:43:50.720 --> 00:43:56.480
[Guest 2]: which is maybe a book, writing a book or making a film, making theater, what happens is there are

00:43:56.480 --> 00:44:01.920
[Guest 2]: a lot of phases during that process where you are going by conviction. You're not able to take

00:44:01.920 --> 00:44:07.120
[Guest 2]: feedback because you have to decide whether you want to do this or not. And that is where I think

00:44:07.120 --> 00:44:12.480
[Guest 2]: many a times people have a problem because it's not there. But it's going on with conviction. But

00:44:12.480 --> 00:44:18.400
[Guest 1]: after the movie comes, it feels like this is not it. And also I'll tell you, with Mr. Javed,

00:44:18.400 --> 00:44:22.640
[Guest 1]: you know, all the work that I did. Once I remember, he has a poem in Tarkash,

00:44:22.640 --> 00:44:27.920
[Guest 1]: gin gin ke sikke haath mera khurdura hua, jaati rahi lumps ki nami, bura hua. You know,

00:44:27.920 --> 00:44:34.320
[Guest 1]: I was so busy counting money that at some point I lost the sensitivity. I lost all feeling. Very

00:44:34.320 --> 00:44:39.200
[Guest 1]: often when we and see, we've been through this thing. We are sensitive to the world outside.

00:44:39.200 --> 00:44:43.440
[Guest 1]: We're sensitive to all reaction. I mean, we react to everything else that's happening around us,

00:44:43.440 --> 00:44:49.840
[Guest 1]: which creates, which in some sense, you know, provokes our art or creates our art. After a

00:44:49.840 --> 00:44:53.600
[Guest 1]: point in time when you lose that focus and you move ahead. See, when you talk of cricket also,

00:44:53.600 --> 00:44:58.720
[Guest 1]: here's this guy who's bowling really, really well. But there's also this guy who is just

00:44:59.280 --> 00:45:06.320
[Guest 1]: practicing the bowling 24-7. He's also a good player. Now, your assumption, Zakir also said

00:45:06.320 --> 00:45:12.320
[Guest 1]: a big thing in the show, that your success, you measure it from where you started.

00:45:12.960 --> 00:45:18.480
[Guest 1]: Don't measure it from where you have reached. Because if I say today that I am rich and then

00:45:18.480 --> 00:45:23.280
[Guest 1]: I will compare with Ambani, then where am I? But from where I started. If you can at least

00:45:23.280 --> 00:45:27.920
[Guest 1]: do some kind of a progress report of what you have done, where you've reached, look at what you I

00:45:27.920 --> 00:45:31.680
[Guest 1]: mean, look at where you've reached. Or I mean, Amit, when he talks about his podcasting, I hate

00:45:31.680 --> 00:45:37.120
[Guest 1]: the 30 minute format, because today the format has evolved to where it is. But it has also evolved

00:45:37.120 --> 00:45:42.000
[Guest 1]: because you've got feedback, you've got constant, I mean, I think you build so many feedback loops

00:45:42.000 --> 00:45:46.960
[Amit Varma]: and building feedback loops into anything you do. But you know, okay, so I'll all of which is

00:45:46.960 --> 00:45:53.200
[Amit Varma]: correct. And I agree with that. But I'll add a layer to that, which is that with a sportsperson,

00:45:53.200 --> 00:45:57.360
[Amit Varma]: with a cricketer, if you're a batsman, there is one metric, it is an objective metric, it is how

00:45:57.360 --> 00:46:01.360
[Amit Varma]: many runs you're making, you can get unlucky in one innings or whatever, but over a decent sample

00:46:01.360 --> 00:46:06.560
[Amit Varma]: size, pata chal jata hai ki, you know, kya level hai. With art, the problem is that there are two

00:46:06.560 --> 00:46:14.080
[Amit Varma]: different kinds of metrics, right? And one is the metric of just immediate popularity, that you're

00:46:14.080 --> 00:46:18.080
[Amit Varma]: getting the talis now, you're getting the numbers now, and that is one kind of metric and you do

00:46:18.080 --> 00:46:23.120
[Amit Varma]: what and you you know, you focus on that and you do whatever it takes to get you there. The other

00:46:23.120 --> 00:46:28.800
[Amit Varma]: is a metric where you are really sort of not catering to that mass, where you're saying ki

00:46:29.360 --> 00:46:33.360
[Amit Varma]: mujhe niche pakarna hai ya mujhe niche banana hai from scratch, there's no niche there, but I will

00:46:33.360 --> 00:46:38.000
[Amit Varma]: make it, you know, people who have a certain sensibility who will appreciate what you do,

00:46:38.000 --> 00:46:42.080
[Amit Varma]: where you say that those numbers don't matter. And therefore, the metric of mass popularity

00:46:42.080 --> 00:46:48.080
[Amit Varma]: doesn't matter. And you're catering to something else, which at that moment is invisible. Like,

00:46:48.080 --> 00:46:53.760
[Amit Varma]: for example, if I had to go by the mass popularity method by what I the feedback I was getting

00:46:53.760 --> 00:46:58.640
[Amit Varma]: through the feedbacks loop I had, everybody would have said do one hour episodes. In fact,

00:46:58.640 --> 00:47:04.000
[Amit Varma]: initially do 20 minute episodes, you know, the point that I do the long episodes that I do

00:47:04.000 --> 00:47:10.240
[Amit Varma]: is because I stuck to saying that I will do what I want to do. And, you know, and that will attract

00:47:10.240 --> 00:47:15.200
[Amit Varma]: audience of a similar sensibility to me. And the only way I can become good at it is by doing it

00:47:15.200 --> 00:47:20.320
[Amit Varma]: again and again. So even if I'm initially there is no feedback in that direction, I have to keep

00:47:20.320 --> 00:47:24.480
[Guest 1]: doing it. But that Amitna is somewhere that I'm saying that see that that that feedback that was

00:47:24.480 --> 00:47:30.320
[Guest 1]: coming to you was not listener feedback. It was supposed people who know podcasting, when no one

00:47:30.320 --> 00:47:34.720
[Guest 1]: knew podcasting at that time in India. That's true. It's the Balaji problem of Netflix. Wherever any

00:47:34.720 --> 00:47:38.720
[Guest 1]: place you go now in OTT, there is a set of people who thought they knew storytelling and boss,

00:47:38.720 --> 00:47:43.680
[Guest 1]: we used to know GC. GC's format was different, GC's pattern was different, GC was appointment

00:47:43.680 --> 00:47:48.720
[Guest 1]: viewing. Now it's a choice. Now if you apply that metric somewhere else, you went by your

00:47:48.720 --> 00:47:55.840
[Guest 1]: conviction, but ultimately the conviction got ratification by today that those mad fans of

00:47:55.840 --> 00:47:59.680
[Guest 1]: yours everywhere. I mean, I see those meetups that are happening in cities where you're traveling.

00:47:59.680 --> 00:48:06.000
[Guest 1]: It is that ratification. It is Sathe being called by Sachin to his house saying imitate me. That

00:48:06.000 --> 00:48:10.640
[Guest 2]: is the ultimate ratification. But you know, Amit, you're making a very, very important point and

00:48:10.640 --> 00:48:16.640
[Guest 2]: that is something that you suffer because you put your marketing lens. I remember having a

00:48:16.640 --> 00:48:21.360
[Guest 2]: conversation with Vijay Tendulkar, the great playwright and you know that thanks to Pune,

00:48:21.360 --> 00:48:31.440
[Guest 2]: right? I became friends with Tendulkar. You know every Tendulkar boss. So thanks to that background

00:48:31.440 --> 00:48:36.560
[Guest 2]: and knowing people from the theater industry, Tendulkar, Dubey had kind of become my personal

00:48:36.560 --> 00:48:40.800
[Guest 2]: friends in my house in Bandra. They would come, they would have a drink with me, share stories

00:48:40.800 --> 00:48:47.200
[Guest 2]: from when he wrote Gidhade and Ghashiram Kotwal. And he used to always tell me when I used to ask

00:48:47.200 --> 00:48:54.400
[Guest 2]: him that, you know, what drove your writing? He said, mala hai vata. This is what I wanted to

00:48:54.400 --> 00:49:01.840
[Guest 2]: tell a story. Now, the moment you go into consumer feedback and you put your marketing hat and then

00:49:01.840 --> 00:49:06.400
[Guest 2]: you do a quintessential marketing thing that has been taught to us, what does the youth want?

00:49:08.800 --> 00:49:13.760
[Guest 2]: Jab se main youth tha abhi tak, the only question in marketing conferences, what does the youth

00:49:13.760 --> 00:49:19.840
[Guest 2]: want? But the moment you go into the lens of what the audience wants, I think you start killing your

00:49:19.840 --> 00:49:26.320
[Guest 2]: creativity. Because the genesis of creativity is coming from what I have felt from the surroundings

00:49:26.320 --> 00:49:30.800
[Guest 2]: in my Nature Nurture journey. And I am now putting it into a format which is called art,

00:49:30.800 --> 00:49:36.000
[Guest 2]: whether it's performing art or whatever it is. And in that process, now when I put a lens of

00:49:42.560 --> 00:49:47.360
[Guest 2]: defeats the purpose. And the problem is your first creative work is what you feel.

00:49:47.360 --> 00:49:56.160
[Guest 2]: And unfortunately, most creative work after that is what people want. When you turn into a marketer

00:49:56.160 --> 00:50:01.280
[Guest 2]: from a creative and very few creative people are able to maintain that integrity, probably because

00:50:01.280 --> 00:50:06.400
[Guest 2]: they've got success in a big way in the initial phase of their career because of the original

00:50:06.400 --> 00:50:11.520
[Guest 2]: stuff that they created, that they can afford to follow their creative field. The moment you go

00:50:11.520 --> 00:50:18.640
[Guest 2]: that, you know, my market research tells me that 15 to 24 require this kind of humor.

00:50:20.400 --> 00:50:24.240
[Guest 2]: And I think that the point that you make there is very critical is that

00:50:24.240 --> 00:50:45.120
[Guest 2]: how does a creative person figure this challenge out? And that challenge for a creative remains forever.

00:50:45.120 --> 00:50:50.800
[Guest 1]: No, no, but see that's what I'm saying that there has to be, so do not give in to the fact of

00:50:50.800 --> 00:50:57.920
[Guest 1]: oh, the market is asking for this. But I'm saying, over a period of time, you get a set of people

00:50:59.120 --> 00:51:04.800
[Guest 1]: who you know are giving you, like, I mean, you know, you have a set of people who you will

00:51:04.800 --> 00:51:10.480
[Guest 1]: turn to for advice. We'll occasionally have those conversations, right? And I think building this

00:51:10.480 --> 00:51:15.440
[Guest 1]: virtuous circle around you is an important thing. The second thing which is really important is,

00:51:15.440 --> 00:51:21.040
[Guest 1]: I think is, a great cricketer should be able to play all three formats, true or not true?

00:51:21.040 --> 00:51:22.480
[Guest 1]: Not true because it's a different sport.

00:51:22.480 --> 00:51:25.600
[Guest 1]: Exactly, right? Now, that's what I'm saying. So, is he not a great cricketer?

00:51:26.320 --> 00:51:30.240
[Guest 1]: If he didn't serve, no. So, is it a matter of conviction or is it a matter of choice?

00:51:31.120 --> 00:51:35.600
[Guest 1]: So, I'm just saying that he knows how to play cricket. He's playing very well in the test.

00:51:36.480 --> 00:51:41.680
[Guest 1]: One couldn't play. He didn't play T20. He's playing T20 very well. The other one couldn't play. Now,

00:51:41.680 --> 00:51:46.960
[Guest 1]: is he, therefore, I'm saying that, see, success is not the lens of, it's not the measure on this.

00:51:46.960 --> 00:51:52.320
[Guest 1]: Ultimately, it has to be, I know this craft and I'm doing enough with the craft. I tried this. I

00:51:52.320 --> 00:51:57.520
[Guest 1]: tried this. I mean, I'm telling you, I'm such a big believer in experimentation and trying new

00:51:57.520 --> 00:52:02.480
[Guest 1]: things, which is actually exactly the opposite. We have this thing all the time. You do a lot.

00:52:03.840 --> 00:52:09.040
[Guest 1]: You know, if you don't do it, where will you see that new world? If Amit hadn't started clear

00:52:09.040 --> 00:52:14.800
[Guest 1]: writing, I mean, I'm still dying to see your TikTok course, which we were doing on WhatsApp.

00:52:14.800 --> 00:52:20.480
[Guest 1]: Because I want to know what was your view on it. Even today, when I'm in Dubai on another phone,

00:52:20.480 --> 00:52:25.040
[Guest 1]: I'm watching TikTok because I want to know what is that short form format? Is there anything I

00:52:25.040 --> 00:52:30.080
[Guest 1]: could do there? Should I do it? Not for money. The minute commerce enters the equation is very

00:52:30.080 --> 00:52:35.120
[Guest 1]: different. Just for the second, I mean, I was doing this play. What was it? It was just testing.

00:52:35.120 --> 00:52:40.480
[Guest 1]: Can I do it? It's completely different. It's a mad challenge. I won't get the money. It's a theater,

00:52:40.480 --> 00:52:45.440
[Guest 1]: but it's a learning process. And he does the same. You do the same. Commerce lens,

00:52:45.440 --> 00:52:50.080
[Guest 1]: for Satya, it's not a commerce lens because for him, it's a thing. I could have slept for so long.

00:52:52.560 --> 00:52:57.600
[Guest 2]: That is so true. I do it. There's a time when he was doing 20 shows a month. And then,

00:52:57.600 --> 00:53:04.960
[Guest 1]: now I'm tired. Should I do it? Make it? No. And that is him because that time away,

00:53:04.960 --> 00:53:09.200
[Guest 1]: when he's sitting at home and he does these meetings in Pune, or he's doing, you know,

00:53:09.200 --> 00:53:16.640
[Guest 1]: work around spot is when you're actually fermenting new ideas, create, that is the joy. That I think

00:53:16.640 --> 00:53:21.600
[Guest 2]: is really the best part of the process. And I think, you know, consumer feedback is a problem

00:53:21.600 --> 00:53:27.120
[Guest 2]: for creative. Big problem. And I would like to believe that in the past during, even in Bollywood,

00:53:27.120 --> 00:53:31.840
[Guest 2]: if you say the, you know, time when Raj Kapoor and, you know, your metric of failure was only

00:53:31.840 --> 00:53:37.600
[Guest 2]: box office. People didn't, it was not like the social media technology changed the game completely

00:53:37.600 --> 00:53:41.200
[Guest 2]: because now you are getting negative feedback from people who have no understanding. They've

00:53:41.200 --> 00:53:46.240
[Guest 2]: not even seen your work. And that's a problem because today, if Raj Kapoor made a bad film

00:53:46.240 --> 00:53:51.280
[Guest 2]: or, you know, Prithviraj Kapoor did some bad play or whatever. It wasn't fun. That's all the

00:53:51.280 --> 00:53:57.920
[Guest 2]: feedback we used to get. Today, the problem is that the creative is afraid to cross the creative boundary.

00:53:57.920 --> 00:54:02.880
[Guest 2]: Because he's saying, no, this is on social media. These people curse. I'll make a meme of this type,

00:54:02.880 --> 00:54:07.360
[Guest 2]: that will work better. And I think the biggest challenge, the good thing about technology,

00:54:07.360 --> 00:54:12.560
[Guest 2]: we discovered more creative people. That was the good thing. But I think good creative people

00:54:12.560 --> 00:54:18.960
[Guest 2]: are going to get scared to put out newer forms of creative work only because it's not popular.

00:54:18.960 --> 00:54:23.200
[Amit Varma]: So when I used to teach my podcasting course, I remember at one point, somebody asked a question,

00:54:23.200 --> 00:54:28.560
[Amit Varma]: sir, where are the gaps in the market? And I was like, boss, this is a very wrong view.

00:54:28.560 --> 00:54:32.960
[Amit Varma]: Because if there are gaps in the market, a million people will go for them, find them,

00:54:32.960 --> 00:54:40.240
[Amit Varma]: do whatever. The point is, the only thing that makes you unique among the 7 billion people on

00:54:40.240 --> 00:54:44.640
[Amit Varma]: the planet is you. So you just be authentic to yourself and do what you have to do. Now,

00:54:44.640 --> 00:54:51.200
[Amit Varma]: the thing with feedback loops also is that they take a long period of time. Like honestly, Roshan,

00:54:51.200 --> 00:54:57.040
[Amit Varma]: even with my podcast first three or four years, even, I had no idea that I was doing something

00:54:57.040 --> 00:55:00.800
[Amit Varma]: which was really valued by people. It was just, you know, I liked it, I kept doing it, I got some

00:55:00.800 --> 00:55:05.600
[Amit Varma]: feedback, I felt good. It was only after COVID when I said, okay, whoever wants to, you know,

00:55:05.600 --> 00:55:11.120
[Amit Varma]: contribute financially to the show, you can do so, open that page. Suddenly, month one, I was like,

00:55:11.120 --> 00:55:16.160
[Amit Varma]: like, what is happening, you know, that's when I kind of realized. And then with the clear writing

00:55:16.160 --> 00:55:19.760
[Amit Varma]: course, when people signed up, that's when I kind of began to interface with those people and

00:55:19.760 --> 00:55:24.240
[Amit Varma]: realized that it means so much to so many people. But otherwise, it is a completely dispersed thing.

00:55:24.240 --> 00:55:29.840
[Amit Varma]: And I have no idea. But once I know, then I can double down on the things that I find of value in

00:55:29.840 --> 00:55:36.000
[Amit Varma]: it. And what you're saying what creators Vikram is so true, because if you are chasing the numbers,

00:55:36.000 --> 00:55:41.200
[Amit Varma]: everybody is going to the lowest common denominator. And secondly, today, we are in a space

00:55:41.200 --> 00:55:46.240
[Amit Varma]: where AI is going to do that way better than us. You know, if you look at and friends,

00:55:46.240 --> 00:55:50.640
[Amit Varma]: abhi toh GPT 3.5 chal raha hai, but GPT 4, some friends of mine have seen it in private, and they

00:55:50.640 --> 00:55:55.120
[Amit Varma]: are raving about it. They're saying it's mad. And, you know, we are recording this at the

00:55:55.760 --> 00:56:02.080
[Amit Varma]: start of December, but what we so even the GPT we see today is not at the level it will, you know,

00:56:02.080 --> 00:56:07.760
[Amit Varma]: it's going to just exponentially get better. So I think for an artist, you know, you have to

00:56:07.760 --> 00:56:11.840
[Amit Varma]: not chase gaps in the market, as it were, but just do.

00:56:13.040 --> 00:56:16.400
[Guest 1]: To add to what you said, or whatever, this morning, I saw something incredible. There's a

00:56:16.400 --> 00:56:20.400
[Guest 1]: show called Wednesday, which is currently taking the world by storm and whatever, you know, and,

00:56:20.400 --> 00:56:26.560
[Guest 1]: and I wonder who watches what nowadays, because it's crazy. Now, Jenna Ortega, this girl who's

00:56:26.560 --> 00:56:34.000
[Guest 1]: in the show, who in the last 10 days, has gone to from 2.3 million followers to 12.3, a million

00:56:34.000 --> 00:56:39.040
[Guest 1]: followers every day she's added, she's just acting in the show. She's a brilliant actress, what she's

00:56:39.040 --> 00:56:43.440
[Guest 1]: doing, I think she really gives so much to the character, but it's directed by Tim Burton.

00:56:44.960 --> 00:56:48.240
[Guest 1]: Tim Burton's vision is visible in every frame that you see.

00:56:48.240 --> 00:56:50.480
[Guest 1]: Aur ek zamane mein woh cult tha, mass nahi tha.

00:56:50.480 --> 00:56:53.760
[Guest 1]: Boss, Edward Scissorhand, etc. ke time pe aap keh rahe the, oh,

00:56:53.760 --> 00:56:58.640
[Guest 1]: Beetlejuice, kya ho raha hai. But that's what I'm saying, but you know, he has conviction in himself.

00:56:59.600 --> 00:57:04.080
[Guest 1]: Jenna Ortega will find it very difficult after Wednesday gets over, though it'll obviously run

00:57:04.080 --> 00:57:08.320
[Guest 1]: into multiple seasons, to, that when she does her next work, if it doesn't get this appreciated,

00:57:08.320 --> 00:57:13.280
[Guest 1]: because this dopamine hitna of constant like, like, like, like jo hai, which is why I say that

00:57:13.280 --> 00:57:17.760
[Guest 1]: over a period of time, mein toh yaar kuch 15 ghar ghar chuka ho, toh mujhe pata hota hai,

00:57:17.760 --> 00:57:23.920
[Guest 1]: I've been, you know, people say, oh, so, I said, nahi, boss, aapko success dikhti hai, failure

00:57:23.920 --> 00:57:28.880
[Guest 1]: mujhe dik chuka hai, bohot baar dikha hai, chhoti chhoti cheezon mein dikha hai, yeh show banaya,

00:57:28.880 --> 00:57:34.240
[Guest 1]: nahi chala, yeh kara nahi chala, film mein kara nahi chala, yeh hua. But the fact is that I'm

00:57:34.240 --> 00:57:40.240
[Guest 1]: constantly keeping up with this whole space of saying, try new things, have a set of people,

00:57:40.240 --> 00:57:44.480
[Guest 1]: and it's not, I'm not asking you for feedback, but even if I have the conversation with you,

00:57:44.480 --> 00:57:50.080
[Guest 2]: there is enough to take away. See, the problem is that everybody, whether you are a theater actor,

00:57:50.080 --> 00:57:55.920
[Guest 2]: whether you are, you know, say, Bollywood actor, whether you are probably, you know, making,

00:57:56.800 --> 00:58:02.560
[Guest 2]: you're a sculptor, everybody can't get an 8 billion audience. And this is a standard problem

00:58:02.560 --> 00:58:08.000
[Guest 2]: that we have even in sport. And many times I go and I'm talking about the game, everybody says,

00:58:08.000 --> 00:58:13.280
[Guest 2]: sir, you are cricket, you don't know how wrestlers are suffering, you don't know how chess players

00:58:13.280 --> 00:58:19.280
[Guest 2]: are suffering. And I said, you know, you have to understand that every sport has a different

00:58:19.280 --> 00:58:25.280
[Guest 2]: audience. And just because something is 10,000 crores doesn't mean 50 crore is bad. A small

00:58:25.280 --> 00:58:29.920
[Guest 2]: scale company doesn't, you know, just because Reliance is a big company doesn't mean a bearings

00:58:29.920 --> 00:58:37.200
[Guest 2]: manufacturer in Pune is bad. He has his own space, Reliance has his own space, so you're saying that

00:58:37.200 --> 00:58:46.400
[Guest 2]: everybody has to become a big company. There won't be any space for MSMEs. Similarly, there is a chess market, but you have to think whether you are at the top of that chess market or not.

00:58:46.400 --> 00:58:52.240
[Guest 2]: But unfortunately, everybody wants to become cricket and a, you know, 10 billion dollar company. And

00:58:52.240 --> 00:58:56.800
[Guest 2]: there is no argument, right? If we are going to play Khokho or we are going to play Atta Patta or

00:58:56.800 --> 00:59:01.680
[Guest 2]: we are going to try to make these, you know, sports that have been there in India for a while

00:59:01.680 --> 00:59:06.480
[Guest 2]: successful, why are we looking at cricket? Let's make a successful 5 crore enterprise.

00:59:06.480 --> 00:59:12.000
[Guest 2]: Let's make that sport, you know, successful in that particular segment and therefore get the

00:59:12.000 --> 00:59:17.200
[Guest 2]: economics right in that segment. But unfortunately, every conference you go to, you know, this is the

00:59:17.200 --> 00:59:22.640
[Guest 2]: problem. Badminton should be the new cricket. It doesn't happen like that. Couple of thoughts on this.

00:59:22.640 --> 00:59:26.720
[Amit Varma]: One, of course, is from the Creator Economy, where Kevin Kelly wrote that famous essay 12 years back,

00:59:26.720 --> 00:59:32.960
[Amit Varma]: Thousand True Fans, where the thesis is, don't think of it anymore in terms of winner takes all,

00:59:32.960 --> 00:59:38.160
[Amit Varma]: which the entertainment industry has been before that the people at the 1% will make all the money

00:59:38.160 --> 00:59:43.760
[Amit Varma]: and the rest are strugglers in Versova cafes. But instead, you know, if you get 1000 true fans

00:59:43.760 --> 00:59:49.040
[Amit Varma]: who are willing to pay $100 a year for your work, that's enough. And we see that on Substack with

00:59:49.040 --> 00:59:55.440
[Amit Varma]: some the standard subscription model is $100 a year and you have many previously unknown

00:59:55.440 --> 01:00:01.280
[Amit Varma]: Substackers making a decent amount of money with that. That's sort of one aspect of it that you

01:00:01.280 --> 01:00:08.000
[Amit Varma]: don't have to necessarily reach out to all those people. So, you know, so, on this, there's this

01:00:08.000 --> 01:00:13.680
[Guest 1]: new podcast, which is being done by the Bombay Shaving, I hope I don't take the wrong company's

01:00:13.680 --> 01:00:17.840
[Guest 1]: name, but you know, the Shantanu, this guy who's an entrepreneur has been doing and he's talking

01:00:17.840 --> 01:00:23.120
[Guest 1]: about entrepreneurship. And one person in that podcast we interviewed said this saying that,

01:00:23.120 --> 01:00:29.360
[Guest 1]: you know, a tennis player, right? The he said that 100 tennis player earns about half a million

01:00:29.360 --> 01:00:34.080
[Guest 1]: dollars and the top guy earns this. And he did exactly this. He said, look at badminton,

01:00:34.080 --> 01:00:38.080
[Guest 1]: where the number one player earns X and the number 100 perhaps earns nothing.

01:00:39.040 --> 01:00:45.280
[Guest 1]: Said, you know, the comparison, you should know the extent to which you are playing.

01:00:45.280 --> 01:00:49.120
[Guest 1]: That whole thing which you used to occasionally which you joked about saying that Mr. Gavaskar

01:00:49.120 --> 01:00:53.120
[Guest 1]: is very upset even today about the fact that he didn't make money from cricket.

01:00:53.840 --> 01:00:57.680
[Guest 1]: Because the time when he was there, cricket was not a money-making sport.

01:00:57.680 --> 01:01:01.680
[Guest 1]: Now today, it's such a money-making sport. But he made the maximum money in his tennis

01:01:01.680 --> 01:01:05.120
[Unknown]: which he forgets. Which is what I'm saying, that's what I keep saying. But Satish, that's what I'm

01:01:05.120 --> 01:01:12.880
[Guest 1]: saying that do not, see because I was an anchor to a very large degree, I often had to stay in

01:01:12.880 --> 01:01:18.160
[Guest 1]: this thing of, he has a car, he has this, he has that. I don't know what it was, I don't know whether

01:01:18.160 --> 01:01:24.240
[Guest 1]: it is the Lucknow or Bringing, whatever it is, but I never compared. But I said, where have I come from?

01:01:24.240 --> 01:01:28.240
[Guest 2]: Exactly, Roshan, the problem here is in cricket as well as in Bollywood.

01:01:28.240 --> 01:01:28.960
[Guest 2]: Absolutely.

01:01:28.960 --> 01:01:32.480
[Guest 2]: In cricket as well as in IPL, only 20 people are earning multimillion salaries.

01:01:32.480 --> 01:01:33.200
[Guest 2]: Correct.

01:01:33.200 --> 01:01:40.400
[Guest 2]: The remaining 100 players are in the small range. Similarly, even in our entertainment industry,

01:01:40.400 --> 01:01:44.960
[Guest 2]: you take the 20 Bollywood stars out, you take the 5 or 6 TV stars out,

01:01:44.960 --> 01:01:50.160
[Unknown]: rest are not going to make that much money. But the aspiration of those guys is to become Ranveer

01:01:50.160 --> 01:01:55.200
[Guest 2]: Singh. Now, the moment you start comparing yourself with Ranveer Singh's annual income,

01:01:55.840 --> 01:02:04.560
[Guest 2]: you have stopped growing. The problem is, in every field, you want everyone in that entire

01:02:04.560 --> 01:02:11.360
[Guest 2]: ecosystem to become the unicorn of that field. And unless we reconcile to the fact that even the

01:02:11.360 --> 01:02:17.600
[Guest 2]: smaller guys are viable, as long as you are viable, as long as you know that you can continue

01:02:17.600 --> 01:02:22.480
[Guest 2]: building good sportsmen or good artists in that sphere, you should be happy. But then if you also

01:02:22.480 --> 01:02:29.600
[Guest 2]: want 150 million likes like Cristiano Ronaldo, when you are playing probably Kabaddi in Tiruchirappalli,

01:02:29.600 --> 01:02:34.480
[Guest 2]: then you should be worried about how your success in that state is, rather than getting followers.

01:02:34.480 --> 01:02:37.280
[Guest 1]: Of course, see what's happening with startups, right? I mean, over the last three years,

01:02:37.280 --> 01:02:42.320
[Guest 1]: and also this thing about suddenly, I mean, everybody will join whichever new trend is

01:02:42.320 --> 01:02:46.560
[Guest 1]: coming. But now startups, remember that I used to joke and say that in the late 80s,

01:02:46.560 --> 01:02:50.400
[Guest 1]: if you didn't do anything, people would ask you, what do you do? You would say, I work in PR.

01:02:51.120 --> 01:02:54.400
[Unknown]: Then a few years later, you would turn and say, what do you do? I work in event management.

01:02:54.400 --> 01:02:59.920
[Guest 1]: Right? It continued. And last was, I work in digital. Now it was, I'm an entrepreneur.

01:03:00.640 --> 01:03:05.600
[Guest 1]: Everybody is a startup entrepreneur. And even if you lose your job, how will you get credibility?

01:03:05.600 --> 01:03:10.720
[Guest 1]: I'm a startup. I'm just working on my startup. Now, my problem, and because of my thing,

01:03:10.720 --> 01:03:16.560
[Guest 1]: saying investor, because I invested a bunch of startups or whatever. There's a set of emails every

01:03:16.560 --> 01:03:22.800
[Guest 1]: day. And I promise you, they're a case study. Because I have seen your life, I want to become

01:03:22.800 --> 01:03:27.680
[Guest 1]: you, blah, blah, blah, blah. I've got this idea that no one else has ever had. You know, and ideas

01:03:27.680 --> 01:03:32.720
[Guest 1]: are a dime a dozen. Where's the implementation? What will you do? The true entrepreneur will be

01:03:32.720 --> 01:03:36.800
[Guest 1]: seen right now when this funding winter is going on. Yeah, suddenly there's a big funding.

01:03:36.800 --> 01:03:42.960
[Guest 1]: Now we'll know who's actually in how much water. People, see, the rising tide carries all boats.

01:03:42.960 --> 01:03:48.480
[Guest 1]: But now we'll know when it's coming down, who's in how much water. Right? Suddenly,

01:03:48.480 --> 01:03:52.960
[Guest 1]: those same people who are giving you that $100 million check are not even cutting you. I mean,

01:03:52.960 --> 01:03:57.920
[Guest 1]: they actually say, I'm sorry, no more money. Two of my friends had to exit. I exited a company last

01:03:57.920 --> 01:04:02.400
[Guest 1]: time because I thought I was getting great value. I said, no, no, this is 5x more. Called me two

01:04:02.400 --> 01:04:08.720
[Guest 1]: weeks back and he said, you know, I had to take a haircut and take what you, 30% of what you took,

01:04:08.720 --> 01:04:14.560
[Guest 1]: because they said, market's completely changed. So this thing now of following, chasing that

01:04:14.560 --> 01:04:22.800
[Guest 1]: trend, become a TikTok star, become this, basic talent, first see who that is. I have never taken

01:04:22.800 --> 01:04:33.600
[Amit Varma]: a haircut. And our second, we'll come to Conhead later. You know, you mentioned startup. So I

01:04:33.600 --> 01:04:40.000
[Amit Varma]: remembered the second point I wanted to make with the thousand two fans point, which was that I did

01:04:40.000 --> 01:04:43.920
[Amit Varma]: an episode with Vinay Singhal. Right now, Vinay Singhal is one guy who said, I won't follow the

01:04:44.480 --> 01:04:52.160
[Amit Varma]: trend. He started this company called Stage. Have you heard of? Yeah. So what Stage decided

01:04:52.160 --> 01:04:57.440
[Amit Varma]: was that we will be an OTT for Bharat, but not an OTT for Bharat in terms of Hindi, Punjabi,

01:04:57.440 --> 01:05:04.160
[Amit Varma]: in these major languages, but for the dialects. Now, I had always thought that, you know, that

01:05:04.160 --> 01:05:09.840
[Amit Varma]: with urbanization and the forces of capitalism and people going for scale, that there's going

01:05:09.840 --> 01:05:14.880
[Amit Varma]: to be a certain homogenization, that you grow up in a Haryana village, you have a particular

01:05:14.880 --> 01:05:19.920
[Amit Varma]: dialect, you go to a city, but then your incentives are to learn the languages of the city, which

01:05:19.920 --> 01:05:24.960
[Amit Varma]: could be Hindi, if it's a north city, or it could be English, and gradually dialects die. And

01:05:24.960 --> 01:05:29.360
[Amit Varma]: Vinay's narrative has a lot of this happening in the first part of his life, where he is embarrassed

01:05:29.360 --> 01:05:32.880
[Amit Varma]: of his dialect, he speaks about a struggle learning English, and then he speaks about a struggle

01:05:32.880 --> 01:05:38.640
[Amit Varma]: learning Hindi, you know, and so but he started an OTT for dialects like Haryanvi, Bhojpuri and

01:05:38.640 --> 01:05:42.560
[Amit Varma]: Rajasthani, I think are the three that they have now. And that's worked remarkably well, they've

01:05:42.560 --> 01:05:47.920
[Amit Varma]: got a lakh and a half subscribers at Netflix rates. And I see a movement towards the opposite

01:05:47.920 --> 01:05:52.560
[Amit Varma]: direction now, again, fueled by capitalism, but also with the aid of technology, which is

01:05:52.560 --> 01:05:58.240
[Amit Varma]: empowering individual creators, where a creator can today go out there and say, okay, I am Haryanvi,

01:05:58.240 --> 01:06:03.360
[Amit Varma]: I talk like this, but I'm proud of it, I'm going to own it, you know, I'm not going to try to fit

01:06:03.360 --> 01:06:08.880
[Amit Varma]: in, I don't care where the large market is, I will own it. And those markets are now taking shape,

01:06:08.880 --> 01:06:14.240
[Amit Varma]: like when I spoke about this reverse migration from Bollywood, that earlier Haryanvi kids used to

01:06:14.240 --> 01:06:18.880
[Amit Varma]: come to Bombay, to work in Bollywood, and today they are going back. And I find this very

01:06:18.880 --> 01:06:25.760
[Amit Varma]: interesting, because what this means, to me, is a semi permanent shift away from the mainstream

01:06:25.760 --> 01:06:31.520
[Amit Varma]: being everything, there will still be a mainstream, but it will no longer be everything, that people

01:06:31.520 --> 01:06:37.360
[Amit Varma]: will also have their own ecosystems where, you know, but there'll be dispersed audiences, there'll

01:06:37.360 --> 01:06:43.680
[Amit Varma]: be whatever, but they can form the like, I have my little ecosystems, which I as a consumer,

01:06:43.680 --> 01:06:48.080
[Amit Varma]: which I keep dipping into, like including chess, for example, which you guys might not even know

01:06:48.080 --> 01:06:53.520
[Amit Varma]: are there, and it doesn't matter. And they are big enough to be successful, you no longer need scale.

01:06:53.520 --> 01:06:58.400
[Guest 1]: And they are financially viable. Yeah. No, but are you comfortable with the niche,

01:06:58.400 --> 01:07:04.080
[Guest 1]: that Haryanvi actor going back and working on the stage has to be comfortable currently with

01:07:04.080 --> 01:07:08.800
[Guest 1]: the fact that it will be perhaps a 100 crore economy. Now, if he again goes back to the

01:07:08.800 --> 01:07:13.760
[Guest 1]: Ranveer Singh comparison, he'll be sitting and saying, yaar, yaha ka Hussar Ranveer ban diya, lekin wahan ka kab ban diya.

01:07:13.760 --> 01:07:22.880
[Guest 2]: But kya hai Roshan, jab yeh organize hoega, aur iska evolution hoga, toh uska jo revenue hai, probably will be better than many Bollywood actors here.

01:07:22.880 --> 01:07:31.360
[Guest 2]: Possibly. Forget the top 8-10, but if I am a Haryana ka Ranveer Singh, I will make more money than a whole lot of people in mainstream Bollywood.

01:07:31.360 --> 01:07:36.080
[Amit Varma]: But my point is, you don't have to be Haryana ka Ranveer Singh, you can be Haryana ka whatever, Gajraj Rao.

01:07:36.080 --> 01:07:42.960
[Guest 2]: Absolutely. But the fact that Gajraj Rao can survive and make money in Haryanvi is a great thing.

01:07:42.960 --> 01:07:48.800
[Guest 1]: And the other unique thing that will happen over a period of time is once you get comfortable with

01:07:48.800 --> 01:07:53.040
[Guest 1]: telling stories in your own Basha Boli, as he said, that beautiful line, right?

01:07:53.040 --> 01:08:00.400
[Guest 1]: Ke main apni boli mein, apni dialect mein kahaani batara hu, phir aap dusri cheez karenge, aap pehle toh apni kahaaniya batayenge.

01:08:00.400 --> 01:08:06.560
[Guest 1]: And when the stories are deeply personal, they are absolutely universal. Yeah, right. So when a

01:08:06.560 --> 01:08:12.560
[Guest 1]: parasite suddenly wins an Oscar, it's why? Because, and this is where I believe that AI etc is going to

01:08:12.560 --> 01:08:18.320
[Guest 1]: say, here is a Haryanvi thing, but I'm able to dub it. I'm currently working with two startups,

01:08:18.320 --> 01:08:24.800
[Guest 1]: where these guys are doing dubbing, which is going to sync. So first, it will take any dialect, as

01:08:24.800 --> 01:08:31.680
[Guest 1]: long as the AI has got the ability to translate that, right? So from audio to text, then it'll

01:08:31.680 --> 01:08:37.120
[Guest 1]: take the text, translate it into another language. It'll contextualize with a human individual to see

01:08:37.120 --> 01:08:42.480
[Guest 1]: whether that is working. And then it's going to lay it back in another emotional voice. Now,

01:08:42.480 --> 01:08:47.840
[Guest 1]: imagine what will happen to content then. Then it'll be the success of the story.

01:08:47.840 --> 01:08:53.920
[Guest 1]: And that's what I'm saying. And therefore, going deeply niche is actually going to bring about

01:08:53.920 --> 01:08:58.880
[Guest 2]: something unique. And I'm hoping for that. And I think what it will also do is that if at one

01:08:58.880 --> 01:09:05.760
[Guest 2]: point of time for 100 years, only aspirational cool dudes have been mainstream Bollywood actor,

01:09:05.760 --> 01:09:19.760
[Guest 2]: it will slowly get cut. And suppose I'm a boy from Haryana, I'm seeing that my hero is a Haryana star. And he also has a BMW 7 series, which used to be only with Ranveer Singh.

01:09:19.760 --> 01:09:26.320
[Guest 2]: The moment all those parameters come in my local hero, then my need to relate to Ranveer Singh or

01:09:26.320 --> 01:09:31.040
[Guest 2]: probably any Bollywood actor is much lesser, because I know that my heroes also have it.

01:09:31.040 --> 01:09:41.040
[Guest 2]: And therefore, I think it will kind of equalize. And that is probably the reason the South Indian stars in the past, Rajinikanth wanted to come and do mainstream Hindi films.

01:09:41.040 --> 01:09:43.040
[Guest 1]: They don't want to do it anymore.

01:09:43.040 --> 01:09:49.040
[Guest 2]: Now, why would they want to? They might just want to do it because they want to. We also need a North Indian audience. But now that problem has been solved.

01:09:49.040 --> 01:09:51.040
[Guest 2]: North Indian audience is now watching South Indian films.

01:09:51.040 --> 01:09:59.040
[Guest 1]: The Pushpa you saw, sorry I'm just butting in, but the Pushpa you saw in Hindi, because you saw it in Hindi, was dubbed by Shreyas Talpade.

01:09:59.040 --> 01:10:03.040
[Guest 1]: And dubbed so beautifully, Dharivedi is standing and saying, boss, look at that level of dubbing.

01:10:03.040 --> 01:10:05.040
[Guest 1]: And that's what made the film. They didn't change the film.

01:10:05.040 --> 01:10:06.040
[Guest 1]: Exactly.

01:10:06.040 --> 01:10:10.040
[Guest 1]: And the problem that Bollywood is doing right now, by the way, because so many of my friends tell me this.

01:10:10.040 --> 01:10:14.040
[Guest 1]: They say, now what happens is, boss, they make South type films. No, brother.

01:10:14.040 --> 01:10:17.040
[Guest 1]: It runs there. It's their narrative.

01:10:17.040 --> 01:10:20.040
[Guest 1]: He can tie a lungi and slide his slippers there.

01:10:20.040 --> 01:10:21.040
[Guest 2]: Exactly.

01:10:21.040 --> 01:10:23.040
[Guest 2]: If you do it in Bombay, someone will slap you.

01:10:23.040 --> 01:10:30.040
[Guest 2]: The thing is, sir, conventionally in India, from Punjab and North India, we look, because they had a celebratory culture.

01:10:30.040 --> 01:10:32.040
[Guest 2]: They wore nice clothes.

01:10:32.040 --> 01:10:35.040
[Guest 2]: So an aspiration was made that we have to become this.

01:10:35.040 --> 01:10:44.040
[Guest 2]: But now what is it that if people who look the same in every state are speaking in Haryanvi or Gujarati, then my aspiration is over.

01:10:44.040 --> 01:10:48.040
[Guest 2]: I don't want to do a Bollywood film because my hero is sitting here.

01:10:48.040 --> 01:10:51.040
[Guest 2]: And I think that will be a very, very good thing for India.

01:10:51.040 --> 01:10:58.040
[Guest 1]: The appetite in this city at the moment, I say, I was telling Amit about the concert market or whatever.

01:10:58.040 --> 01:11:03.040
[Guest 1]: Saying that there are three cities in India that make money, which is Delhi, Bombay and Ahmedabad.

01:11:03.040 --> 01:11:06.040
[Guest 1]: These are the only ones where you can make money off big concerts.

01:11:06.040 --> 01:11:12.040
[Guest 1]: But today, who's stopping you from taking those 20 and 90 other cities where there is the money.

01:11:12.040 --> 01:11:16.040
[Guest 1]: You just need to figure out what is the model and take those shows there and make money.

01:11:16.040 --> 01:11:17.040
[Guest 1]: But no one does it.

01:11:17.040 --> 01:11:19.040
[Guest 1]: Everybody wants to make a name here.

01:11:19.040 --> 01:11:21.040
[Guest 1]: There are hundreds of places.

01:11:21.040 --> 01:11:24.040
[Guest 1]: And India, the opportunity that is India right now.

01:11:24.040 --> 01:11:30.040
[Guest 1]: Honestly, and people say this thing that okay, for everything that is wrong in the last so many years of governance or whatever.

01:11:30.040 --> 01:11:34.040
[Guest 1]: The growth of the small city when you think about it is mind blowing.

01:11:34.040 --> 01:11:35.040
[Guest 1]: And what have you given them?

01:11:35.040 --> 01:11:36.040
[Guest 1]: You gave them infrastructure.

01:11:36.040 --> 01:11:37.040
[Guest 1]: You gave them IT.

01:11:37.040 --> 01:11:40.040
[Guest 1]: And now boss, the road is open.

01:11:40.040 --> 01:11:41.040
[Guest 1]: They have the hunger.

01:11:41.040 --> 01:11:46.040
[Guest 1]: They have the hunger and hiring people from smaller cities.

01:11:46.040 --> 01:11:49.040
[Guest 1]: People say, oh, there's a Lucknow quota.

01:11:49.040 --> 01:11:51.040
[Guest 2]: This is the ultimate thing.

01:11:51.040 --> 01:11:54.040
[Guest 2]: I say, recruit people who don't know English.

01:11:54.040 --> 01:11:57.040
[Amit Varma]: More hunger, more desire.

01:11:57.040 --> 01:12:00.040
[Amit Varma]: There's a selection bias that they've come so far as to reach you.

01:12:00.040 --> 01:12:02.040
[Guest 2]: So they wanted that much more.

01:12:02.040 --> 01:12:04.040
[Amit Varma]: Look at sport and look at Haryana.

01:12:04.040 --> 01:12:08.040
[Guest 2]: I mean, today, no fast bowler from urban places will go beyond 120.

01:12:08.040 --> 01:12:11.040
[Guest 2]: Because he's not seen distance that long.

01:12:11.040 --> 01:12:24.040
[Amit Varma]: So I'm very, I'm very struck by what Roshan said about, you know, that tell your story in Haryanvi and all stories are universal and it will reach everywhere.

01:12:24.040 --> 01:12:29.040
[Amit Varma]: And I'm reminded of Ayn Rand's quote about how the smallest minority is an individual.

01:12:29.040 --> 01:12:32.040
[Amit Varma]: And I think the biggest niche is an individual.

01:12:32.040 --> 01:12:37.040
[Amit Varma]: If you're just true to yourself, it will reach everybody, which is a big lesson here.

01:12:37.040 --> 01:12:43.040
[Amit Varma]: And also I could see Vikram's brain working overtime when you mentioned that AI, which will do the dubbing and all that.

01:12:43.040 --> 01:12:44.040
[Amit Varma]: And what is he thinking?

01:12:44.040 --> 01:12:46.040
[Amit Varma]: It's the age of deepfake.

01:12:46.040 --> 01:12:48.040
[Amit Varma]: Anybody's voice can be done.

01:12:48.040 --> 01:12:51.040
[Amit Varma]: You know, you put an AI to work on all three of us.

01:12:51.040 --> 01:12:53.040
[Guest 2]: We don't need to physically talk and have this conversation.

01:12:53.040 --> 01:12:55.040
[Guest 2]: AI will have the conversation.

01:12:55.040 --> 01:12:58.040
[Guest 2]: AI will make Tony Gregg's voice.

01:12:58.040 --> 01:12:59.040
[Guest 1]: Yeah, correct.

01:12:59.040 --> 01:13:08.040
[Guest 1]: I'm telling you, Vikram is always working towards what is the highest output with the least input.

01:13:08.040 --> 01:13:10.040
[Amit Varma]: I am the king of minimal input.

01:13:10.040 --> 01:13:11.040
[Amit Varma]: That's leveraging.

01:13:11.040 --> 01:13:12.040
[Amit Varma]: That's wise.

01:13:12.040 --> 01:13:15.040
[Unknown]: And I sat with him and said, Vikram, let's do this.

01:13:15.040 --> 01:13:17.040
[Guest 1]: You do it.

01:13:17.040 --> 01:13:21.040
[Guest 1]: He said to me, he'll support me to death.

01:13:21.040 --> 01:13:23.040
[Guest 1]: But it's crazy.

01:13:23.040 --> 01:13:24.040
[Guest 1]: My frustration.

01:13:24.040 --> 01:13:26.040
[Guest 1]: Why would you do this?

01:13:26.040 --> 01:13:28.040
[Guest 1]: Let's do it.

01:13:28.040 --> 01:13:32.040
[Unknown]: Because I can see the effort.

01:13:32.040 --> 01:13:34.040
[Guest 1]: I'm sorry, I've got it.

01:13:34.040 --> 01:13:42.040
[Guest 1]: When we went to celebrate his 40th, my wife said, Vikram, you can look happy.

01:13:42.040 --> 01:13:44.040
[Guest 1]: I am.

01:13:44.040 --> 01:13:49.040
[Unknown]: Look, sir, I don't like this surprise concept.

01:13:49.040 --> 01:13:50.040
[Guest 2]: You had a surprise party.

01:13:50.040 --> 01:13:52.040
[Guest 2]: He had a surprise party.

01:13:52.040 --> 01:13:56.040
[Unknown]: Look, I say all this, but control is very important to me.

01:13:56.040 --> 01:13:59.040
[Unknown]: If you have given a surprise, then it is not in my control.

01:13:59.040 --> 01:14:02.040
[Unknown]: This means I am nothing.

01:14:02.040 --> 01:14:06.040
[Unknown]: So you can't surprise your 50th party.

01:14:06.040 --> 01:14:08.040
[Guest 2]: I don't plan a surprise party.

01:14:08.040 --> 01:14:09.040
[Amit Varma]: For yourself.

01:14:09.040 --> 01:14:11.040
[Unknown]: It will be a surprise if you execute it.

01:14:11.040 --> 01:14:14.040
[Unknown]: Oh God.

01:14:14.040 --> 01:14:19.040
[Amit Varma]: So before we get back to your chronology, I wanted to double click on something else that you said, which was fascinating.

01:14:19.040 --> 01:14:27.040
[Amit Varma]: Where you said that what you need to get ahead in life is to have 5 friends, 5 business contacts, and you get by.

01:14:27.040 --> 01:14:34.040
[Amit Varma]: And what I was thinking about that is that one, I sort of agree with the importance of friends.

01:14:34.040 --> 01:14:38.040
[Amit Varma]: So I have realized late in life that one has to be intentional.

01:14:38.040 --> 01:14:39.040
[Amit Varma]: Like I've lost touch with so many people.

01:14:39.040 --> 01:14:40.040
[Amit Varma]: Same laziness.

01:14:40.040 --> 01:14:42.040
[Amit Varma]: Who's going to make the effort?

01:14:42.040 --> 01:14:43.040
[Amit Varma]: I'll have to write an email.

01:14:43.040 --> 01:14:44.040
[Amit Varma]: Why?

01:14:44.040 --> 01:14:45.040
[Amit Varma]: You know, he remembers me.

01:14:45.040 --> 01:14:50.040
[Amit Varma]: So but now I try to make more of an effort to, you know, stay in touch with friends and all of that.

01:14:50.040 --> 01:14:54.040
[Amit Varma]: But I am wondering about the role of intentionality in this.

01:14:54.040 --> 01:15:01.040
[Amit Varma]: Like even in whatever little career I had, you know, I was never a person who wanted to go out networking.

01:15:01.040 --> 01:15:08.040
[Amit Varma]: That meet people and hand out a visiting card in the age where visiting cards existed and do all of that.

01:15:08.040 --> 01:15:09.040
[Amit Varma]: That just wasn't for me.

01:15:09.040 --> 01:15:12.040
[Amit Varma]: I was like, if I like talking to you, I'll talk to you.

01:15:12.040 --> 01:15:14.040
[Amit Varma]: Otherwise, you know, I'm not going to make the effort.

01:15:14.040 --> 01:15:18.040
[Amit Varma]: But how important is intentionality to this?

01:15:18.040 --> 01:15:23.040
[Amit Varma]: Because it's one thing to say that these are the friends who help me and these are the people who help my business.

01:15:23.040 --> 01:15:26.040
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, it's one thing to come at it post-facto.

01:15:26.040 --> 01:15:29.040
[Amit Varma]: And it's another to say that I need to cultivate friends.

01:15:29.040 --> 01:15:31.040
[Amit Varma]: I need to stay in touch with my five friends.

01:15:31.040 --> 01:15:35.040
[Amit Varma]: I need to stay in touch with, you know, I need to make business contacts.

01:15:35.040 --> 01:15:37.040
[Amit Varma]: Because I don't know when they will come in handy.

01:15:37.040 --> 01:15:40.040
[Amit Varma]: And that second attitude is very difficult for me.

01:15:40.040 --> 01:15:42.040
[Amit Varma]: Though in the context of friends, I'm trying to do it.

01:15:42.040 --> 01:15:45.040
[Amit Varma]: In the context of business, my mind just doesn't think like that.

01:15:45.040 --> 01:15:48.040
[Amit Varma]: So, how much is that intentionality important?

01:15:48.040 --> 01:15:50.040
[Guest 2]: So, I struggled with the same.

01:15:50.040 --> 01:15:52.040
[Guest 2]: Because I came from a middle-class Pune family.

01:15:52.040 --> 01:15:59.040
[Guest 2]: And which, you know, even your skills that you have, you're not supposed to display it.

01:15:59.040 --> 01:16:01.040
[Guest 2]: Let your work speak for itself.

01:16:01.040 --> 01:16:03.040
[Guest 2]: It's not important to market yourself.

01:16:03.040 --> 01:16:05.040
[Guest 2]: This is where I come from.

01:16:05.040 --> 01:16:08.040
[Guest 2]: So, even I thought that intentionally making friends with someone,

01:16:08.040 --> 01:16:13.040
[Guest 2]: this means that you're taking work out of me, this is not the right lens you should go.

01:16:13.040 --> 01:16:16.040
[Guest 2]: And I continued with this thought for a long time.

01:16:16.040 --> 01:16:18.040
[Guest 2]: So, whatever 4-5 friends I had, they were natural friends.

01:16:18.040 --> 01:16:21.040
[Guest 2]: It was fun to spend time with them in Vaishali.

01:16:21.040 --> 01:16:24.040
[Guest 2]: And it automatically happened that I invested in them.

01:16:24.040 --> 01:16:25.040
[Guest 2]: There was no intentionality.

01:16:25.040 --> 01:16:29.040
[Guest 2]: But then I met a very interesting guy who's a very close friend of mine.

01:16:29.040 --> 01:16:31.040
[Guest 2]: Whose name is Sunandan Lele.

01:16:31.040 --> 01:16:36.040
[Guest 2]: And he's somebody, you know, one of the most eminent cricket journalists

01:16:36.040 --> 01:16:39.040
[Guest 2]: that has been in our part of the world.

01:16:39.040 --> 01:16:44.040
[Guest 2]: Most importantly, he's somebody who is what I call Jag Mitra.

01:16:44.040 --> 01:16:48.040
[Guest 2]: He has close to 5000 friends across the world.

01:16:48.040 --> 01:16:51.040
[Guest 2]: There is no cricketer who's not his best friend.

01:16:51.040 --> 01:16:53.040
[Guest 2]: And I used to go on tours.

01:16:53.040 --> 01:16:56.040
[Guest 2]: I started touring since 2002-2003.

01:16:56.040 --> 01:16:59.040
[Guest 2]: Up until Tendulkar retired actively in 2013.

01:16:59.040 --> 01:17:01.040
[Guest 2]: And then 3-4 years and then I stopped touring.

01:17:01.040 --> 01:17:04.040
[Guest 2]: And I was like amazed by this guy.

01:17:04.040 --> 01:17:07.040
[Unknown]: That he intentionally...

01:17:07.040 --> 01:17:09.040
[Guest 2]: See, he loves people.

01:17:09.040 --> 01:17:12.040
[Guest 2]: So, he doesn't have to do it from life.

01:17:12.040 --> 01:17:14.040
[Guest 2]: But he told me one thing.

01:17:14.040 --> 01:17:17.040
[Guest 2]: He said, Vikram, when are we happy?

01:17:17.040 --> 01:17:21.040
[Guest 2]: I said, when somebody acknowledges us.

01:17:21.040 --> 01:17:23.040
[Guest 2]: There is a deep engagement.

01:17:23.040 --> 01:17:25.040
[Guest 2]: Someone says something good to me.

01:17:25.040 --> 01:17:26.040
[Guest 2]: Basic things, right?

01:17:26.040 --> 01:17:28.040
[Guest 2]: What is happiness?

01:17:28.040 --> 01:17:32.040
[Guest 2]: Positive thoughts, engagement, relationships, acknowledgement, meaning of life.

01:17:32.040 --> 01:17:37.040
[Guest 2]: On these 5 pillars, happiness, dopamine production is dependent.

01:17:37.040 --> 01:17:40.040
[Guest 2]: So, if you like these things,

01:17:40.040 --> 01:17:42.040
[Guest 2]: it means others like it too.

01:17:42.040 --> 01:17:45.040
[Guest 2]: So, if you are giving happiness to someone,

01:17:45.040 --> 01:17:48.040
[Unknown]: then why do you have intention and guilt in it?

01:17:48.040 --> 01:17:51.040
[Guest 2]: If randomly you have to go to Roshan and say,

01:17:51.040 --> 01:17:54.040
[Guest 2]: Roshan, I think what you did was nice.

01:17:54.040 --> 01:17:56.040
[Guest 2]: Even if it is false.

01:17:56.040 --> 01:17:59.040
[Guest 2]: But if it makes somebody happy, this is the greatest charity you can do.

01:17:59.040 --> 01:18:01.040
[Guest 2]: That's the perspective he got in me.

01:18:01.040 --> 01:18:05.040
[Guest 2]: And I realized that spending time with him,

01:18:05.040 --> 01:18:07.040
[Guest 2]: he would go out of the way.

